{"title_page": "Primo Magnani", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Primo Magnani\n| image          = Cycling at the 1920 Summer Olympics, Italian team, team pursuit.jpg\n| image_size     = 250px\n| caption        = Magnani at the 1920 Summer Olympics\n| fullname       = Primo Magnani\n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1892|3|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Pavia]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1969|6|17|1892|3|31|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = [[Milan]], Italy\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = [[Track cycling|Track]]\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry| {{ITA}} }}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[track cycling]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[Cycling at the 1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Antwerp]] | [[Cycling at the 1920 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team pursuit|Team pursuit]]}}\n| show-medals = yes\n| updated     = \n}}\n\n'''Primo Magnani''' (31 March 1892 &ndash; 17 June 1969) was an [[Italy|Italian]] [[racing cyclist]] and Olympic champion in [[track cycling]].\n\nHe won a gold medal in the [[team pursuit]] at the [[1920 Summer Olympics]] in [[Antwerp]] (with [[Arnaldo Carli]], [[Ruggero Ferrario]] and [[Franco Giorgetti]]).<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ma/primo-magnani-1.html |title=Primo Magnani Olympic Results |accessdate=2013-12-25 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref> Magnani also participated in the [[Cycling at the 1920 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 50 kilometres|50 kilometres competition]] but his exact result is unknown.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cycling Archives|21658}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Track Team Pursuit Men}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magnani, Primo}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1969 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Italian track cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1920 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:People from Pavia]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in cycling]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1920 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lombardy]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Primo Magnani\n| image          = Cycling at the 1920 Summer Olympics, Italian team, team pursuit.jpg\n| image_size     = 250px\n| caption        = Magnani at the 1920 Summer Olympics\n| fullname       = Primo Magnani\n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1892|3|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Pavia]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1969|6|17|1892|3|31|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = [[Milan]], Italy\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = [[Track cycling|Track]]\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry| {{ITA}} }}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[track cycling]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[Cycling at the 1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Antwerp]] | [[Cycling at the 1920 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team pursuit|Team pursuit]]}}\n| show-medals = yes\n| updated     = \n}}\n\n'''Primo Magnani''' (31 March 1892 &ndash; 17 June 1969) was an [[Italy|Italian]] [[racing cyclist]] and Olympic champion in [[track cycling]].\n\nHe won a gold medal in the [[team pursuit]] at the [[1920 Summer Olympics]] in [[Antwerp]] (with [[Arnaldo Carli]], [[Ruggero Ferrario]] and [[Franco Giorgetti]]).<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ma/primo-magnani-1.html |title=Primo Magnani Olympic Results |accessdate=2013-12-25 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref> Magnani also participated in the [[Cycling at the 1920 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 50 kilometres|50 kilometres competition]] but his exact result is unknown.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cycling Archives|21658}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Track Team Pursuit Men}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magnani, Primo}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1969 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Italian track cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1920 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:People from Pavia]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in cycling]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1920 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lombardy]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primo_Magnani"}
{"title_page": "New York University College of Arts & Science", "text_new": "{{Advert|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = NYU College of Arts and Science\n| image = NYU CAS logo.png\n| established = 1832\n| dean = [[Gene Andrew Jarrett]]\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| parent = [[New York University]]\n| enrollment = 7,660\n| colors = Mayfair Violet<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nyu.edu/content/dam/nyu/cmsTeam/documents/NYUGraphStandards.pdf |title=New York University Graphic Standards and Logo Usage Guide, second edition, February 2010|publisher=New York University|format=PDF |access-date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> {{color box|#57068C}}\n| address = 32 Waverly Pl, New York, NY 10003\n| city = [[New York City]]\n| state = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| postalcode = 10003\n| country = U.S.\n| website = {{url|cas.nyu.edu}}\n}}[[File:Silver Center1.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Silver Center for Arts and Science]]\n\nThe [[New York University]] '''College of Arts & Science''' (commonly referred to as '''C.A.S.''') is the primary [[liberal arts college]] of [[New York University]]. It is among New York University's most selective individual schools. \n\nAs the oldest and largest school at NYU, the College of Arts & Science currently enrolls 7,660 undergraduate students (as of 2017). The College of Arts and Science offers [[Bachelor of Arts]] (B.A.) and [[Bachelor of Science]] (B.S.) degrees.\n\nFour NYU Arts & Science departments ranked in Top 10 of Shanghai Academic Rankings 2019 of World Universities by Academic Subjects ([[Economics]], [[Politics]], [[Psychology]], and [[Sociology]]).<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n[[File:History Image.jpg|300px|right]]\n\n==History==\nThe history of the College of Arts and Science begins with the founding of the university by a number of prominent New Yorkers, led by [[Albert Gallatin]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/libraries-and-research-centers/leonard-lauder-research-center/programs-and-resources/index-of-cubist-art-collectors/gallatin|title=Gallatin, Albert E.|date=8 November 2017}}</ref> a member of [[Thomas Jefferson|Jefferson]]\u2019s cabinet. Unlike other institutions at the time, it was to be nonsectarian and to produce a different sort of elite citizen, not born to privilege but set apart for leadership by talent and effort. To that end, it was to provide what the 19th century called \"Useful Knowledge.\"\n\nFounded in 1862, undergraduate liberal arts education at NYU took place in two locations-University College (and the [[New York University Tandon School of Engineering|Engineering School]]) at the Heights and the College on [[Washington Square Park|Washington Square]] before the 1970s, when the College underwent yet another major transformation. In response to financial pressures, the Heights campus closed in 1973 and University College merged with [[New York University|Washington Square College]]. The new institution, which is now known simply as the College of Arts and Science.\n\n[[File:CAS Graduation.jpg|thumb|300px|right|College of Arts & Science graduation ceremony]]\n\n==Academics==\nThe college provides an undergraduate liberal arts education through its Core Curriculum, which is designed to prepare students to thrive in their major programs of study. Undergraduate students may select from 66 majors as well as a host of accelerated Bachelor's-Master's and pre-professional programs offered through 30 departments, most of which also offer courses at NYU's 13 study away sites. Additionally, students may select from over 60 minors offered within the college; they may also choose 40 cross-school minors at other schools within NYU.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{main|List of New York University alumni|List of New York University faculty}}\n\n'''Academics:'''\n\n[[File:Howard Zinn at lectern cropped.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Howard Zinn]], Class of 1967]]\n[[File:Martha Nussbaum wikipedia 10-10.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Martha Nussbaum]], Class of 1969]]\n* [[Edward J. Bloustein]], B.A. 1948; former president of Rutgers University, New Brunswick, New Jersey\n* [[Lionel Casson]], B.A. 1934; classicist, archeologist, professor emeritus at New York University\n* [[Howard Crosby (minister)|Howard Crosby]], B.A. 1844; Presbyterian minister and NYU chancellor 1870\u20131881\n* [[Richard Davidson]], B.A. 1972; Professor of Psychology at [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n* [[Morris Janowitz]], B.A. 1941; founder of [[military sociology]], professor at [[University of Chicago]]\n* [[Richard Joel]], B.A. 1972; current president of [[Yeshiva University]], New York City\n* [[Joseph Keller]], B.A. 1943; 1988 [[National Medal of Science]] recipient\n* [[Paul Kurtz]], B.A. 1948; Professor Emeritus of Philosophy at the [[State University of New York at Buffalo]]\n* [[Ellen Langer]], B.A. 1970; Professor of Psychology at [[Harvard University]]\n* [[Peter D. Lax]], B.A. 1947; mathematician, 2005 [[Abel Prize]] recipient, 1986 [[National Medal of Science]] recipient\n* [[Sherwin B. Nuland]], B.A. 1951; bioethicist, author of ''How We Die''\n* [[Martha Nussbaum]], B.A. 1969; philosopher, professor at [[University of Chicago]]\n* [[Leonard Peikoff]], B.A. 1954; philosopher, leading advocate of [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivism]]\n* [[Howard Zinn]], B.A. 1951; historian, author of ''[[A People's History of the United States]]''\n\n'''Arts, acting, and entertainment:'''\n\n* [[Milton Babbitt]], B.A. 1935; composer, 1986 [[MacArthur Fellow]]\n* [[Bob Balaban]], B.A. 1977; actor\n* [[Neil Diamond]] (Did not graduate); musician\n* [[Tom Ford]] (Did not graduate); fashion designer and film director\n* [[William Gaines]], B.A. 1948; founder of [[MAD Magazine]]\n* [[Ilana Glazer]], B.A. 2009; co-star and co-creator of the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Broad City]]''\n* [[Ethan Hawke]] (Did not graduate); actor\n* [[Tom Kirdahy]], B.A. 1985; Theater producer and activist\n* [[Stanley Kramer]], B.A. 1933; film director\n* [[Ken Leung]], B.A. 1992; actor\n* [[Dave Liebman]], B.A. 1967; jazz musician\n* [[Leonard Maltin]], B.A. 1973; film critic\n* [[Glen Mazzara]], B.A. 1989; television producer\n* [[Alan Menken]], B.A. 1972; musical theater and film composer\n* [[Meg Ryan]], B.A. 1982; actor\n[[File:Martin Scorsese Berlinale 2010 (cropped).jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Martin Scorsese]], Class of 1964]]\n* [[Martin Scorsese]], B.A; 1964; film director, 2006 recipient of [[Academy Award for Best Director]]\n\n'''Authors and writers:'''\n[[File:Frank mccourt 20060912.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Frank McCourt]], Class of 1957]]\n* [[Warren Adler]], B.A. 1947; author of ''[[The War of the Roses (novel)|The War of the Roses]]''\n* [[Caleb Carr]], B.A. 1977; author\n[[File:Elizabeth Gilbert at TED.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Elizabeth Gilbert]], Class of 1991]]\n* [[Elizabeth Gilbert]], B.A. 1991; author of ''[[Eat, Pray, Love]]''\n* [[Joseph Heller]], B.A. 1948; author of ''[[Catch-22]]''\n* [[Ira Levin]], B.A. 1950; author\n* [[Frank McCourt]], B.A. 1957; 1997 [[Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography]] recipient, author of ''[[Angela's Ashes]]''\n* [[Cynthia Ozick]], B.A. 1930; author\n* [[Kira Peikoff]], B.A. 2007; author and journalist\n* [[Charles Simic]], B.A. 1967; 1984 [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Fellow]], Recipient of 1990 [[Pulitzer Prize for Poetry]], 15th [[Poet Laureate Consultant in Poetry to the Library of Congress|United States Poet Laureate]]\n\n'''Business:'''\n\n[[File:Maria Bartiromo.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Maria Bartiromo]], Class of 1987]]\n* [[Maria Bartiromo]], B.A. 1987; [[Fox Business Network]] television journalist\n* [[Clive Davis]], B.A. 1953; founder of [[Arista Records]]\n* [[Marvin Davis]], B.S. 1947; owner of [[Denver Broncos]], billionaire, industrialist\n* [[Jack Dorsey]] (Did not graduate); co-founder of [[Twitter]] and [[Square, Inc.]]\n* [[Arthur Frommer]], B.A. 1950; tourism industry writer\n* [[Scott Harrison (charity founder)|Scott Harrison]], B.A. 1998; founder and CEO of the non-profit 