eacher, religious leader, social reformer\n* [[Steven Boghos Derounian]], B.A. 1938; US Congressman\n* [[William Henry Draper, Jr.]], B.A. 1916; first [[United States Permanent Representative to NATO|U.S. Permanent Representative to NATO]]\n* [[Fernando Ferrer]], B.A. 1972; former Bronx Borough president and 2005 Democratic nominee for Mayor of New York\n* [[Henry Grunwald (editor)|Henry Grunwald]], B.A. 1944; U.S. ambassador; former managing editor of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine and [[editor in chief]] of [[Time, Inc.]] \n* [[Sean Hannity]] (did not graduate); political commentator\n* [[Frank L. Howley]], B.S. 1925; brigadier general, commandant of the American sector of Berlin\n* [[Jacob Javits]], B.A. 1923; US Senator from New York from 1957 to 1981\n* [[Samuel Levy]], B.A. 1894; Manhattan Borough President\n* [[Martha Roby]], B.A. 1998; US Congresswoman\n* [[Albert del Rosario]], B.S. 1960; former Philippine ambassador to the US. Currently the Philippine Foreign Affairs Secretary\n[[File:Howard cosell 1975.JPG|thumb|alt=|[[Howard Cosell]], Class of 1938]]\n'''Science and technology:'''\n* [[Balamurali Ambati]], B.A. 1991; youngest person ever to become a physician\n* [[Evelyn Berezin]], B.S. 1951; computer engineer\n* [[Eugene Braunwald]], B.A. 1949; cardiologist\n* [[Humayun Chaudhry]], B.A., 1986; president and CEO, [[Federation of State Medical Boards]]\n* [[Avery Fisher]], B.S. 1929; inventor of the [[transistorized]] [[Electronic amplifier|amplifier]] and the first [[stereophonic sound|stereo]] [[radio]]-[[phonograph]], noted [[philanthropist]]\n* [[Neil Garg]], B.S. 2000; Professor of Chemistry at [[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Chris Harrison (computer scientist)|Chris Harrison]], B.S. 2005; computer scientist and entrepreneur, assistant professor at [[Carnegie Mellon University]]\n* [[Henry Sherwood Lawrence]], B.A. 1938; immunologist\n* [[Alfred Vail]], B.A. 1836; inventor\n* [[George Wald]], B.A. 1927; recipient of 1967 [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]]\n\n'''Sports:'''\n\n* [[Marv Albert]], B.A. 1965; sportscaster\n* [[Howard Cann]], B.A. 1920; 1968 Naismith Basketball Hall of Fame Inductee\n* [[Howard Cosell]], B.A. 1938; sportscaster\n* [[Carol Heiss]], B.A. 1961; gold medal winner, Olympic Winter Games 1960\n* [[Mika'il Sankofa]], B.A. 1988; fencer, Olympic Gold Medalist\n* [[Dolph Schayes]], B.S. 1948, [[List of NBA champions|NBA champion]] ([[1955 NBA Finals|1955]]), 12\u00d7 [[List of NBA All-Stars|NBA All-Star]], [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] Inductee\n* [[Ed Smith (American football)|Ed Smith]], B.A. 1934; model for [[Heisman Trophy]]\n* [[George Spitz]], B.A. 1934; world record high jumper\n* [[Colin Cassady]], B.S.; WWE wrestler\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official Website|http://www.cas.nyu.edu}}\n* [http://www.nyu.edu/admissions.html Admission information]\n* [http://www.nyu.edu/academics.html Academics]\n* [http://www.nyu.edu/research.html Research]\n\n{{New York University}}\n\n{{coord|40.73023|N|73.99569|W|source:placeopedia|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New York University College of Arts and Science}}\n[[Category:New York University schools|Arts and Science]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1832]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges at universities in the United States]]\n[[Category:1832 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Advert|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = NYU College of Arts and Science\n| image = NYU CAS logo.png\n| established = 1832\n| dean = [[Gene Andrew Jarrett]]\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| parent = [[New York University]]\n| enrollment = 7,660\n| colors = Mayfair Violet<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nyu.edu/content/dam/nyu/cmsTeam/documents/NYUGraphStandards.pdf |title=New York University Graphic Standards and Logo Usage Guide, second edition, February 2010|publisher=New York University|format=PDF |access-date=August 10, 2015}}</ref> {{color box|#57068C}}\n| city = [[New York City]]\n| state = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| country = U.S.\n| website = {{url|cas.nyu.edu}}\n}}[[File:Silver Center1.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Silver Center for Arts and Science]]\n\nThe [[New York University]] '''College of Arts & Science''' (commonly referred to as '''C.A.S.''') is the primary [[liberal arts college]] of [[New York University]]. As the oldest and largest school at NYU, the College of Arts & Science currently enrolls 7,660 undergraduate students (as of 2017). The College of Arts and Science offers [[Bachelor of Arts]] (B.A.) and [[Bachelor of Science]] (B.S.) degrees.\n\n[[File:History Image.jpg|300px|right]]\n\n==History==\nThe history of the College of Arts and Science begins with the founding of the university by a number of prominent New Yorkers, led by [[Albert Gallatin]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/libraries-and-research-centers/leonard-lauder-research-center/programs-and-resources/index-of-cubist-art-collectors/gallatin|title=Gallatin, Albert E.|date=8 November 2017}}</ref> a member of [[Thomas Jefferson|Jefferson]]\u2019s cabinet. Unlike other institutions at the time, it was to be nonsectarian and to produce a different sort of elite citizen, not born to privilege but set apart for leadership by talent and effort. To that end, it was to provide what the 19th century called \"Useful Knowledge.\"\n\n[[File:CAS Graduation.jpg|thumb|300px|right|College of Arts & Science graduation ceremony]]\n\n==Academics==\nThe college provides an undergraduate liberal arts education through its Core Curriculum, which is designed to prepare students to thrive in their major programs of study. Undergraduate students may select from 66 majors as well as a host of accelerated Bachelor's-Master's and pre-professional programs offered through 30 departments, most of which also offer courses at NYU's 13 study away sites. Additionally, students may select from over 60 minors offered within the college; they may also choose 40 cross-school minors at other schools within NYU.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{main|List of New York University alumni|List of New York University faculty}}\n\n'''Academics:'''\n\n[[File:Howard Zinn at lectern cropped.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Howard Zinn]], Class of 1967]]\n[[File:Martha Nussbaum wikipedia 10-10.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Martha Nussbaum]], Class of 1969]]\n* [[Edward J. Bloustein]], B.A. 1948; former president of Rutgers University, New Brunswick, New Jersey\n* [[Lionel Casson]], B.A. 1934; classicist, archeologist, professor emeritus at New York University\n* [[Howard Crosby (minister)|Howard Crosby]], B.A. 1844; Presbyterian minister and NYU chancellor 1870\u20131881\n* [[Richard Davidson]], B.A. 1972; Professor of Psychology at [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n* [[Morris Janowitz]], B.A. 1941; founder of [[military sociology]], professor at [[University of Chicago]]\n* [[Richard Joel]], B.A. 1972; current president of [[Yeshiva University]], New York City\n* [[Joseph Keller]], B.A. 1943; 1988 [[National Medal of Science]] recipient\n* [[Paul Kurtz]], B.A. 1948; Professor Emeritus of Philosophy at the [[State University of New York at Buffalo]]\n* [[Ellen Langer]], B.A. 1970; Professor of Psychology at [[Harvard University]]\n* [[Peter D. Lax]], B.A. 1947; mathematician, 2005 [[Abel Prize]] recipient, 1986 [[National Medal of Science]] recipient\n* [[Sherwin B. Nuland]], B.A. 1951; bioethicist, author of ''How We Die''\n* [[Martha Nussbaum]], B.A. 1969; philosopher, professor at [[University of Chicago]]\n* [[Leonard Peikoff]], B.A. 1954; philosopher, leading advocate of [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivism]]\n* [[Howard Zinn]], B.A. 1951; historian, author of ''[[A People's History of the United States]]''\n\n'''Arts, acting, and entertainment:'''\n\n* [[Milton Babbitt]], B.A. 1935; composer, 1986 [[MacArthur Fellow]]\n* [[Bob Balaban]], B.A. 1977; actor\n* [[Neil Diamond]] (Did not graduate); musician\n* [[Tom Ford]] (Did not graduate); fashion designer and film director\n* [[William Gaines]], B.A. 1948; founder of [[MAD Magazine]]\n* [[Ilana Glazer]], B.A. 2009; co-star and co-creator of the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Broad City]]''\n* [[Ethan Hawke]] (Did not graduate); actor\n* [[Tom Kirdahy]], B.A. 1985; Theater producer and activist\n* [[Stanley Kramer]], B.A. 1933; film director\n* [[Ken Leung]], B.A. 1992; actor\n* [[Dave Liebman]], B.A. 1967; jazz musician\n* [[Leonard Maltin]], B.A. 1973; film critic\n* [[Glen Mazzara]], B.A. 1989; television producer\n* [[Alan Menken]], B.A. 1972; musical theater and film composer\n* [[Meg Ryan]], B.A. 1982; actor\n[[File:Martin Scorsese Berlinale 2010 (cropped).jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Martin Scorsese]], Class of 1964]]\n* [[Martin Scorsese]], B.A; 1964; film director, 2006 recipient of [[Academy Award for Best Director]]\n\n'''Authors and writers:'''\n[[File:Frank mccourt 20060912.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Frank McCourt]], Class of 1957]]\n* [[Warren Adler]], B.A. 1947; author of ''[[The War of the Roses (novel)|The War of the Roses]]''\n* [[Caleb Carr]], B.A. 1977; author\n[[File:Elizabeth Gilbert at TED.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Elizabeth Gilbert]], Class of 1991]]\n* [[Elizabeth Gilbert]], B.A. 1991; author of ''[[Eat, Pray, Love]]''\n* [[Joseph Heller]], B.A. 1948; author of ''[[Catch-22]]''\n* [[Ira Levin]], B.A. 1950; author\n* [[Frank McCourt]], B.A. 1957; 1997 [[Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography]] recipient, author of ''[[Angela's Ashes]]''\n* [[Cynthia Ozick]], B.A. 1930; author\n* [[Kira Peikoff]], B.A. 2007; author and journalist\n* [[Charles Simic]], B.A. 1967; 1984 [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Fellow]], Recipient of 1990 [[Pulitzer Prize for Poetry]], 15th [[Poet Laureate Consultant in Poetry to the Library of Congress|United States Poet Laureate]]\n\n'''Business:'''\n\n[[File:Maria Bartiromo.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Maria Bartiromo]], Class of 1987]]\n* [[Maria Bartiromo]], B.A. 1987; [[Fox Business Network]] television journalist\n* [[Clive Davis]], B.A. 1953; founder of [[Arista Records]]\n* [[Marvin Davis]], B.S. 1947; owner of [[Denver Broncos]], billionaire, industrialist\n* [[Jack Dorsey]] (Did not graduate); co-founder of [[Twitter]] and [[Square, Inc.]]\n* [[Arthur Frommer]], B.A. 1950; tourism industry writer\n* [[Scott Harrison (charity founder)|Scott Harrison]], B.A. 1998; founder and CEO of the non-profit [[charity: water]]\n* [[Boris Jordan]], B.A. 1988; billionaire, investor\n* [[Henry Kaufman]], B.A. 1948; president of Henry Kaufman & Company, Inc.\n* [[Mildred Robbins Leet]], B.A. 1942; entrepreneur and philanthropist\n* [[Mark Leslie (entrepreneur)|Mark Leslie]], B.A. 1966; venture capitalist and founder of [[Veritas Technologies]]\n* [[Joseph Nacchio]], B.S. 1970; former chairman and chief executive officer of [[Qwest|Qwest Communications International]]\n* [[Marc Rich]] (Did not graduate); commodities trader, billionaire, fugitive \n* [[Larry Silverstein]], B.A. 1952; billionaire, real estate investor\n* [[Sy Syms]], B.A. 1946; founder of Syms Clothing\n* [[Dennis Tito]], B.A. 1962; entrepreneur, [[space tourist]]\n\n'''Journalism:'''\n\n[[File:Ray Suarez.jpg|thumb|alt=|[[Ray Suarez]], Class of 1985]]\n* [[Lynda Baquero]], B.A. 1974; correspondent for [[WNBC]]\n* [[Don Hewitt]], B.A. 1941; television producer, creator of ''[[60 Minutes]]''\n* [[Ray Suarez]], B.A. 1985; broadcast journalist, host of [[Inside Story (TV programme)|Inside Story]] on [[Al Jazeera America]]\n* [[Alvin Toffler]], B.A. 1949; [[futurist]], writer, journalist\n* [[Gene Weingarten]], B.A. 1973; ''[[Washington Post]]'' journalist, two-time [[Pulitzer Prize]] winner\n\n'''Law:'''\n\n* [[Constance Baker Motley]], B.A. 1940; civil rights activist, judge, state senator, [[Borough President]] of [[Manhattan]]\n* [[Evan Chesler]], B.A. 1970; partner and chairman, [[Cravath, Swaine & Moore]]\n* [[Jonathan Lippman]], B.A. 1965; [[Chief Judge of the New York Court of Appeals]]\n* [[Victor Marrero]], B.A. 1963; United States federal senior judge\n* [[Herbert Wachtell]], B.S. 1952; co-founder of the law firm of [[Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & Katz]].\n\n'''Politics and government:'''\n* [[Jerome Anthony Ambro]], B.A. 1955; US Congressman\n* [[Bill de Blasio]], B.A. 1984; 109th [[Mayor of New York City]]\n* [[Irwin Delmore Davidson]], B.S. 1927; US Congressman\n* [[Thomas De Witt Talmage]], B.A. 1853; preacher, religious leader, social reformer\n* [[Steven Boghos Derounian]], B.A. 1938; US Congressman\n* [[William Henry Draper, Jr.]], B.A. 1916; first [[United States Permanent Representative to NATO|U.S. Permanent Representative to NATO]]\n* [[Fernando Ferrer]], B.A. 1972; former Bronx Borough president and 2005 Democratic nominee for Mayor of New York\n* [[Henry Grunwald (editor)|Henry Grunwald]], B.A. 1944; U.S. ambassador; former managing editor of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine and [[editor in chief]] of [[Time, Inc.]] \n* [[Sean Hannity]] (did not graduate); political commentator\n* [[Frank L. Howley]], B.S. 1925; brigadier general, commandant of the American sector of Berlin\n* [[Jacob Javits]], B.A. 1923; US Senator from New York from 1957 to 1981\n* [[Samuel Levy]], B.A. 1894; Manhattan Borough President\n* [[Martha Roby]], B.A. 1998; US Congresswoman\n* [[Albert del Rosario]], B.S. 1960; former Philippine ambassador to the US. Currently the Philippine Foreign Affairs Secretary\n[[File:Howard cosell 1975.JPG|thumb|alt=|[[Howard Cosell]], Class of 1938]]\n'''Science and technology:'''\n* [[Balamurali Ambati]], B.A. 1991; youngest person ever to become a physician\n* [[Evelyn Berezin]], B.S. 1951; computer engineer\n* [[Eugene Braunwald]], B.A. 1949; cardiologist\n* [[Humayun Chaudhry]], B.A., 1986; president and CEO, [[Federation of State Medical Boards]]\n* [[Avery Fisher]], B.S. 1929; inventor of the [[transistorized]] [[Electronic amplifier|amplifier]] and the first [[stereophonic sound|stereo]] [[radio]]-[[phonograph]], noted [[philanthropist]]\n* [[Neil Garg]], B.S. 2000; Professor of Chemistry at [[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n* [[Chris Harrison (computer scientist)|Chris Harrison]], B.S. 2005; computer scientist and entrepreneur, assistant professor at [[Carnegie Mellon University]]\n* [[Henry Sherwood Lawrence]], B.A. 1938; immunologist\n* [[Alfred Vail]], B.A. 1836; inventor\n* [[George Wald]], B.A. 1927; recipient of 1967 [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]]\n\n'''Sports:'''\n\n* [[Marv Albert]], B.A. 1965; sportscaster\n* [[Howard Cann]], B.A. 1920; 1968 Naismith Basketball Hall of Fame Inductee\n* [[Howard Cosell]], B.A. 1938; sportscaster\n* [[Carol Heiss]], B.A. 1961; gold medal winner, Olympic Winter Games 1960\n* [[Mika'il Sankofa]], B.A. 1988; fencer, Olympic Gold Medalist\n* [[Dolph Schayes]], B.S. 1948, [[List of NBA champions|NBA champion]] ([[1955 NBA Finals|1955]]), 12\u00d7 [[List of NBA All-Stars|NBA All-Star]], [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] Inductee\n* [[Ed Smith (American football)|Ed Smith]], B.A. 1934; model for [[Heisman Trophy]]\n* [[George Spitz]], B.A. 1934; world record high jumper\n* [[Colin Cassady]], B.S.; WWE wrestler\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official Website|http://www.cas.nyu.edu}}\n* [http://www.nyu.edu/admissions.html Admission information]\n* [http://www.nyu.edu/academics.html Academics]\n* [http://www.nyu.edu/research.html Research]\n\n{{New York University}}\n\n{{coord|40.73023|N|73.99569|W|source:placeopedia|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New York University College of Arts and Science}}\n[[Category:New York University schools|Arts and Science]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1832]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges at universities in the United States]]\n[[Category:1832 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Andrewmoody71", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_University_College_of_Arts_%26_Science"}
{"title_page": "Mary Creagh", "text_new": "{{short description|British Labour politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{pp|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = [[Chartered Institute of Linguists|FCIL]]\n| name = Mary Creagh\n| caption = Creagh in 2017\n| image = Official portrait of Mary Creagh crop 2.jpg\n| office = Chair of the [[Environmental Audit Select Committee]]\n| term_start = 10 February 2016\n| term_end = 6 November 2019\n| predecessor = [[Huw Irranca-Davies]]\n| successor = [[Philip Dunne (Ludlow MP)|Philip Dunne]]\n| module = {{Collapsed infobox section begin |[[Shadow Cabinet]] positions\n |titlestyle     = border:1px dashed lightgrey}}{{Infobox officeholder\n |embed          = yes\n | office1 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]]\n | leader1 = [[Ed Miliband]]<br />[[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n | 1blankname1 = Shadowing\n | 1namedata1 = [[Justine Greening]]\n | term_start1 = 5 November 2014\n | term_end1 = 12 September 2015\n | predecessor1 = [[Jim Murphy]]\n | successor1 = [[Diane Abbott]]\n | office2 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]]\n | leader2 = [[Ed Miliband]]\n | 1blankname2 = Shadowing\n | 1namedata2 = [[Patrick McLoughlin]]\n | term_start2 = 7 October 2013\n | term_end2 = 5 November 2014\n | predecessor2 = [[Maria Eagle]]\n | successor2 = [[Michael Dugher]]\n | office3 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]\n | leader3 = [[Ed Miliband]]\n | 1blankname3 = Shadowing\n | 1namedata3 = [[Caroline Spelman]]<br />[[Owen Paterson]]\n | term_start3 = 8 October 2010\n | term_end3 = 7 October 2013\n | predecessor3 = [[Hilary Benn]]\n | successor3 = [[Maria Eagle]]\n {{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n| office4 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Wakefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Wakefield]]\n| term_start4 = 5 May 2005\n| term_end4 = 6 November 2019\n| predecessor4 = [[David Hinchliffe]]\n| successor4 = [[Imran Ahmad-Khan]]\n| module = {{Collapsed infobox section begin |[[Islington London Borough Council]] positions\n |titlestyle     = border:1px dashed lightgrey}}{{Infobox officeholder\n |embed          = yes\n | office5 = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] Group Leader<br />on [[Islington London Borough Council]]\n | term_start5 = 2000\n | term_end5 = 2004\n | predecessor5 = Derek Sawyer\n | successor5 = [[Catherine West]]\n | office6 = [[Councillor#United Kingdom|Councillor]] for [[Islington London Borough Council]]\n | 1blankname6 = [[Wards of the United Kingdom|Ward]]\n | 1namedata6 = Highbury West\n | term_start6 = 7 May 1998\n | term_end6 = 5 May 2005\n | successor6 = Theresa Debono\n {{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n| birth_name = Mary Helen Creagh\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|12|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Coventry]], [[Warwickshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = Adrian Pulham\n| children = 1 daughter<br />1 son\n| alma_mater = [[Pembroke College, Oxford]]<br />[[London School of Economics]]\n| website = [http://www.marycreagh.co.uk Official website]\n}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Mary Helen Creagh''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|FCIL}} (born 2 December 1967) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician who represented [[Wakefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Wakefield]] as a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) from [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]] until [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]].\n\nIn 2010, Creagh was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]],<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title = The shadow cabinet in full|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/oct/08/the-shadow-cabinet-in-full|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 4 June 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150605021336/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/oct/08/the-shadow-cabinet-in-full|archive-date = 5 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> before becoming [[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]] in 2013.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title = Labour frontbench reshuffle sees Blairites out and 'brightest of 2010 intake' promoted|url = https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/labour-frontbench-reshuffle-sees-blairites-2348748|accessdate = 4 June 2015|first = Jason|last = Beattie|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150605040853/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/labour-frontbench-reshuffle-sees-blairites-2348748|archive-date = 5 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> In November 2014 she was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]].<ref name=\"bbc-20141105\" />\n\nOn 14 May 2015, Creagh announced she would run for [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]] in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|leadership election]] resulting from [[Ed Miliband]]'s resignation,<ref>{{Cite news|title = Labour leadership: Mary Creagh enters race|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-32742236|website = BBC News|accessdate = 4 June 2015|date = 14 May 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150604031112/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-32742236|archive-date = 4 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> although she later withdrew her candidacy.\n\nShe resigned from the front bench following the election as Labour leader of [[Jeremy Corbyn]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nOf Irish descent, Creagh was born in [[Coventry]],<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/?id=YnAmle9e7AMC&pg=PA963&dq=%22mary+creagh%22+coventry#v=onepage&q=%22mary%20creagh%22%20coventry&f=false\n |author=Robert Waller and Byron Criddle \n |title=The Almanac of British Politics \n |year=2007 \n |publisher=[[Routledge]] \n |work=[[Taylor & Francis]] \n |edition=8 \n |isbn=978-0-203-94691-6 \n |df= \n}}{{dead link|date=August 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> where her father was a car factory worker and her mother a primary school teacher.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} She was educated at the [[Bishop Ullathorne Roman Catholic School|Bishop Ullathorne]] [[Comprehensive School]] in Coventry and read [[Modern Languages]] at [[Pembroke College, Oxford]], graduating as [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA (Oxon)]].<ref>{{cite news\n |newspaper=[[Coventry Telegraph]] \n |url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/cov-kid-mary-creagh-lands-3055134 \n |author=Mary Griffin \n |title=Cov kid Mary Creagh lands key Labour shadow cabinet role \n |date=12 October 2010 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/cov-kid-mary-creagh-lands-3055134 \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> After pursuing European Studies at the [[London School of Economics]] ([[PhD]]),<ref>[http://www.pressreader.com/uk/yorkshire-post/20150311/281943131354556/TextView www.pressreader.com: Dr Mary Creagh MP]</ref> she is a fluent [[French language|French]] and [[Italian language|Italian]] speaker.\n\t\nCreagh worked in [[Brussels]] for four years, first as an [[intern]] at the [[European Parliament]] and then for the [[European Youth Forum]]. She [[Lecturer|lectured]] in entrepreneurship at the [[Cranfield University|Cranfield School of Management]] and served for seven years as a [[Trustee]] of [[Rathbone (charity)|Rathbone]], a national charity.\n\n===Councillor in Islington===\nCreagh was elected as a [[Councillor]] for the [[London Borough of Islington]] in [[1998 Islington Council election|1998]], representing Highbury West ward (renamed Highbury in 2002), and served as the Labour Group Leader for five years during a period when the party was in opposition locally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://londondatastore-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/docs/LBCE_1998-5-7.pdf|title=London Borough Council Elections 7 May 1998|authors=Minors, Michael and Grenham, Dennis|publisher=Greater London Authority|accessdate=26 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008083524/http://londondatastore-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/docs/LBCE_1998-5-7.pdf|archive-date=8 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://files.datapress.com/london/dataset/council-elections-voters-2002/London-Borough-Council-Elections-2002.pdf|title=London Borough Council Elections 2 May 2002|authors=Minors, Michael and Grenham, Dennis|publisher=Greater London Authority|accessdate=26 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220105908/https://files.datapress.com/london/dataset/council-elections-voters-2002/London-Borough-Council-Elections-2002.pdf|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> During this time, she knocked on doors and ran a campaign office for future party leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]].<ref name=\"Yorkshire Evening Post\">{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/mary-creagh-i-want-to-bring-wakefield-out-of-leeds-s-shadow-and-into-the-future-1-9021472 |title=Mary Creagh: 'I want to bring Wakefield out of Leeds's shadow and into the future' |work=Yorkshire Evening Post |date=17 February 2018 |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726234826/https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/mary-creagh-i-want-to-bring-wakefield-out-of-leeds-s-shadow-and-into-the-future-1-9021472 |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> She stood down from [[Islington London Borough Council|Islington Council]] in 2005 upon her election to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dathan|first1=Matt|title=Labour Leadership Race: Who is Mary Creagh?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/labour-leadership-race-who-is-mary-creagh-10251452.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=30 May 2015|location=London|date=14 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518003621/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/labour-leadership-race-who-is-mary-creagh-10251452.html|archive-date=18 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Creagh formally alleged [[cronyism]] in the appointment of the Islington Council [[chief executive]] by five [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] councillors thus triggering an investigation by the [[Standards Board for England]]. After the longest ever investigation by the Standards Board, her complaint was rejected. Creagh was criticised by the [[tribunal]] as being \"heavily influenced by her political motives\" and that she was an \"insensitive witness, lacking in balanced judgment and one who was prepared to make assumptions about honesty and integrity of others without any proper basis\".<ref name=\"Guardian Media Group\">{{cite news|last1=Weaver|first1=Matt|title=Council leader cleared of cronyism charge|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2006/jan/05/localgovernment.politics1|accessdate=30 May 2015|publisher=Guardian Media Group|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530182251/http://www.theguardian.com/society/2006/jan/05/localgovernment.politics1|archive-date=30 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> However, Creagh defended herself saying she \"blew the whistle because I believed the Liberal Democrats were not meeting the standards we expect from people in public office. I invite people to look at my evidence and draw their own conclusions\".<ref name=\"Guardian Media Group\"/>\n\nThe Liberal Democrat councillors involved lost their seats at the 2006 elections, their [[Political party|party]] also lost control of the Council.<ref>{{cite news|title=Election 2006: Islington|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/vote2006/locals/html/au.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924162150/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/vote2006/locals/html/au.stm|archive-date=24 September 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n\n=== Backbencher and early posts: 2005\u20132010 ===\n[[File:Mary Creagh, 2016 Labour Party Conference.jpg|upright|thumb|Creagh speaking at a 2016 Labour Party Conference fringe meeting]]\nCreagh succeeded the retiring [[David Hinchliffe]] as MP for Wakefield. She won the seat in [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Election 2005: Wakefield|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/vote2005/html/602.stm|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051221064526/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/vote2005/html/602.stm|archive-date=21 December 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> with a majority of 5,154, and held the seat \u2013 altered by boundary changes \u2013 with a majority of 1,613 [[2010 United Kingdom general election|five years later]]. She made her [[maiden speech]] in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]] on 25 May 2005 using the occasion to raise issues of poverty in her constituency. She also mentioned locally-born sculptor [[Barbara Hepworth]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm050525/debtext/50525-29.htm#50525-29_spnew0 \n |title=Maiden speech in Hansard \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm050525/debtext/50525-29.htm \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\nShe was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Andy Burnham]], [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport]], from 2006 until June 2009, when she was appointed as an assistant government whip in the Department of Health.<ref name=progress-20130228/>\n\nShe was a member of the [[Human Rights]] [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|Select committee]] from 2005 until 2007. From 2007 to 2009, she was Chair of the Labour Movement for Europe,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://labourmovement.eu/ |title=www.labourmovement.eu |access-date=26 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226040913/http://labourmovement.eu/ |archive-date=26 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> succeeding [[Chris Bryant]] MP and being succeeded by [[Richard Corbett]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]. She is a member of the [[Labour Friends of Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-s-pro-israel-mps-face-wipe-out-1.436505|title=Labour's pro-Israel MPs face wipe-out|publisher=The Jewish Chronicle|date=20 April 2017|access-date=10 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730110854/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-s-pro-israel-mps-face-wipe-out-1.436505|archive-date=30 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn Labour leadership elections, she backed [[Gordon Brown]] in 2007<ref>{{cite news|title=Who's backing Gordon Brown? |publisher=theguardian.com |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/may/17/labourleadership.labour1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2007/may/17/labourleadership.labour1 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |location=London |date=17 May 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[David Miliband]] in May 2010.<ref name=progress-20130228>{{cite web |url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2013/02/28/mary-mary/ |title=Mary, Mary? |publisher=Progress |date=28 February 2013 |accessdate=23 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150615002728/http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2013/02/28/mary-mary/ |archive-date=15 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter entering the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], Creagh campaigned successfully on a number of issues. In 2005, she introduced a Children's Food Bill which sought to introduce minimum nutritional standards for all school meals and take fizzy drinks and sugary snacks out of school vending machines. Both of these measures were accepted by the government and became law under the [[Education and Inspections Act 2006]].<ref>{{cite web\n |title=The Education and Inspections Bill 2006 \n |url=http://www.standards.dfes.gov.uk/new/published/edubill \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.standards.dfes.gov.uk/new/published/edubill \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> In 2006, Creagh launched a campaign aimed at preventing [[scalding]] injuries in the home. She brought together medical experts, campaign groups and victims of scalding injuries to lobby the government to change the building regulations to prevent people being severely scalded by hot water. The coalition pressured the government to make the fitting of a water temperature regulating device, such as a [[thermostatic mixing valve]] (TMV), compulsory in new bathrooms in England. In 2009, after a three-year \"Hot Water Burns Like Fire\" campaign, the Labour government confirmed TMVs were to be a standard fitment in all new bathrooms from April 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotwaterburnslikefire.org.uk/ |title=Hot Water Burns Like Fire |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.hotwaterburnslikefire.org.uk/ |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release\n |url=http://www.politics.co.uk/opinion-formers/press-releases/health/beama-mps-welcome-scalding-campaign-success-$1310419$366174.htm \n |title=BEAMA: MPs welcome scalding campaign success \n |date=10 July 2009 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.politics.co.uk/opinion-formers/press-releases/health/beama-mps-welcome-scalding-campaign-success-%241310419%24366174.htm \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> In 2009, as Vice Chair of the [[All-Party Parliamentary Group]] for the Prevention of Genocide and Other Crimes Against Humanity, Creagh called on Justice Secretary [[Jack Straw]] to tighten British Law so people accused of genocide could be prosecuted in the [[Law of the United Kingdom|UK]]. She said there was an \"impunity gap\" which allowed people accused of terrible crimes in places like [[Rwanda]] and [[Bosnia]] to escape justice and live freely in Britain.<ref>{{cite news\n |title=UK plans new powers on genocide \n |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8139045.stm \n |publisher=BBC News \n |date=7 July 2009 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8139045.stm \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> As a result of this, the government agreed to amend the [[Coroners and Justice Act 2009|Coroner's and Justice Bill]] to tighten the [[United Kingdom legislation|law]] so anyone suspected of [[war crimes]] anywhere throughout the world since 1991 and resident in the UK could be prosecuted in [[Courts of the United Kingdom|UK courts]].<ref>{{cite news\n |publisher=[[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Justice]] \n |title=Jack Straw to strengthen law title \n |date=7 July 2009 \n |url=http://www.justice.gov.uk/news/newsrelease070709b.htm \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.justice.gov.uk/news/newsrelease070709b.htm \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\n=== Shadow Cabinet: 2010\u20132015 ===\nOn 8 October 2010, Creagh was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In February 2011 she secured a House of Commons debate<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Public Forest Estate (England) debate \n |publisher=[[Hansard]] \n |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110202/debtext/110202-0003.htm#11020248002385 \n |date=2 February 2011 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110202/debtext/110202-0003.htm \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> on the government's plans to sell off 85% of [[Forestry in the United Kingdom|public forestry]]. The government subsequently abandoned these plans,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-12488847 |title=Forest sale axed |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |date=16 February 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-12488847 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> it having become clear that the public \"were not happy with the proposals\".<ref>{{cite web\n |publisher=[[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|DEFRA]] \n |title=The future of forestry in England \n |url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2011/02/17/futureforestry/ \n |date=17 February 2011 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2011/02/17/futureforestry/ \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> In 2011, Creagh criticised the decision by the [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]] to cut [[Flood control|flood defence]] spending in real terms by 32%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/house_of_commons/newsid_9392000/9392060.stm |date=9 February 2011 |title=Urgent Question: Flood defences |publisher=BBC News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/house_of_commons/newsid_9392000/9392060.stm |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In addition to her involvement in campaigns calling for the banning of wild animals performing in [[circus]]es,<ref>{{cite news|title=Labour calls for ban on wild animals in circuses |date=19 May 2011 |publisher=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/house_of_commons/newsid_9490000/9490875.stm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/house_of_commons/newsid_9490000/9490875.stm |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> she has opposed the government's policy of badger culling, claiming it was \"anti-science\" and that the option of vaccination should be explored.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Creagh|first1=Mary|title=In pursuing the badger cull, the government is being anti-science|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/aug/26/badger-cull-government-anti-science|website=Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611014757/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/aug/26/badger-cull-government-anti-science|archive-date=11 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[Labour Party (UK) Conference|Labour Party's Annual Conference]] in September 2011, Creagh launched the campaign ''Back the Apple''.<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.youtube.com/watch?v=x2DluFoQlak|title=Back the Apple|publisher=[[YouTube]]|work=[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]|date=24 September 2011|access-date=19 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204132223/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x2DluFoQlak|archive-date=4 December 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> with [[Unite the Union]]. The campaign opposes the government's plan to abolish the [[Agricultural Wages Board]]<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/food-farm/farm-manage/wages/ \n |title=Agricultural employment and wages \n |publisher=DAFTA \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.defra.gov.uk/food-farm/farm-manage/wages/ \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> which sets wages and conditions for thousands of agricultural workers.\n\nIn 2013, Creagh was appointed Shadow Secretary of State for Transport.<ref name=\":1\" /> On 24 March 2014 she and [[Jamie Hanley]] opposed the train fares price increases in [[New Pudsey railway station|New Pudsey]] proposed by [[Patrick McLoughlin]]. The opposition spread throughout 18 [[West Yorkshire]] stations, forcing McLoughlin to scrap the plan.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Telegraph & Argus]] |date=24 March 2014 |accessdate=30 March 2014 |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/11096418.Mary_Creagh_joins_transport_fight_at_New_Pudsey/?ref=var_0 |title=Mary Creagh joins transport fight at New Pudsey |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/11096418.Mary_Creagh_joins_transport_fight_at_New_Pudsey/?ref=var_0 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The same day she took part in the minibus opening ceremony which was hosted by [[Colchester|Colchester Community Volunteer Service]]<ref>{{cite news\n |date=24 March 2014 \n |accessdate=30 March 2014 \n |url=http://www.essexcountystandard.co.uk/news/ecsnews/11097731.All_aboard_the_new_bus_/ \n |title=CCVS celebrates as sixth bus takes to the road \n |author=Wendy Brading \n |newspaper=[[Essex County Standard]] \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.essexcountystandard.co.uk/news/ecsnews/11097731.All_aboard_the_new_bus_/ \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> and two days later accused the government of donating their time into privatising [[East Coast Main Line]] instead of worrying about high fare prices.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/blighty/2014/03/rail-privatisation \n |publisher=The Economist \n |title=Fractious tracks \n |date=26 March 2014 \n |accessdate=30 March 2014 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/https://www.economist.com/blogs/blighty/2014/03/rail-privatisation \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, she became [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]].<ref name=\"bbc-20141105\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29918950 |title=Labour reshuffle: Dugher and Powell promoted by Ed Miliband |publisher=BBC |date=5 November 2014 |accessdate=30 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627120659/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29918950 |archive-date=27 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== Labour leadership candidate ====\nOn 14 May 2015, Creagh announced her candidacy for [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]], after [[Ed Miliband]]'s resignation following the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} On 12 June, Creagh announced that she was withdrawing from the leadership contest. At the time of her announcement, she had secured about 10 nominations from Labour MPs, fewer than any of the other remaining candidates and well short of the 35 required to take part in the final ballot.<ref name=\"BBC News 12 June 2015\">{{cite news | title= Mary Creagh pulls out of Labour leadership race | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-33117505 | author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | date= 12 June 2015 | website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= 12 June 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150614044929/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-33117505 | archive-date= 14 June 2015 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Return to the backbenches: 2015\u20132019===\nAfter the election of Jeremy Corbyn as Labour leader in September 2015, Creagh resigned from the front bench.<ref>{{cite web |title=Andy Burnham and John McDonnell get top jobs in Corbyn's Shadow Cabinet |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=14 September 2015 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/11862774/andy-burnham-shadow-home-secretary-jeremy-corbyn-cabinet.html |accessdate=14 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914222013/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/11862774/andy-burnham-shadow-home-secretary-jeremy-corbyn-cabinet.html |archive-date=14 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> She supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=21 July 2016|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715214543/https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], Creagh was reported as writing to constituents to say that her team had been \u201cspeaking to people in your street\u201d who had told them they had \u201cmore confidence in Theresa May as Prime Minister than Jeremy Corbyn,\u201d predicted a large Tory majority and called for a vote for them as individuals while promising to \u201cwork for a Labour Party that can once again regain your confidence.\u201d The letter was similar to ones sent by [[Joan Ryan]] and [[Gavin Shuker]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/h-lead-labour-friends-israel-chair-among-mps-losing-no-confidence-votes|title=Labour Friends of Israel chair Joan Ryan and Luton South's Gavin Shuker lose no confidence votes|last=Chacko|first=Ben|date=7 September 2018|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=Morning Star|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907202652/https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/h-lead-labour-friends-israel-chair-among-mps-losing-no-confidence-votes|archive-date=7 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n \nOn the BBC programme ''[[Newsnight]]'' (1 December 2015) Creagh argued in favour of military action in Syria, stating: \"ISIL pose a clear threat to Britain\", \"it makes no sense to turn our planes back at the Syrian border\" and \"we must act to keep our country safe\"<ref name=\"BBC Newsnight 01 December 2015\">{{cite news | title= Mary Creagh Newsnight appearance | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06r2q66 | date= 1 December 2015 | publisher= BBC | accessdate= 1 December 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151207183515/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06r2q66 | archive-date= 7 December 2015 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Creagh became chair of the [[Environmental Audit Select Committee|Environmental Audit Committee]].\n\nIn November 2018, Creagh expressed sympathy for [[Angela Smith (South Yorkshire politician)|Angela Smith]] after Smith's [[Constituency Labour Party]] passed a vote of no confidence in her.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/99939/labour-mp-hits-out-hard-left-cabal-after-losing|title=Labour MP hits out at 'hard-left cabal' after losing vote of confidence|last=Schofield|first=Kevin|date=17 November 2018|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=Politics Home|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181117114939/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/99939/labour-mp-hits-out-hard-left-cabal-after-losing|archive-date=17 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2019, Creagh was invited to join the [[Change UK]] breakaway of Labour MPs, but declined.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/eighth-labour-mp-leaves-party-as-jeremy-corbyn-says-quitters-were-elected-on-his-manifesto-1-4875902|title=Eighth Labour MP leaves party as Jeremy Corbyn says quitters were elected on his manifesto|last=Gourtsoyannis|first=Paris|date=20 February 2019|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=The Scotsman|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190613021625/https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/eighth-labour-mp-leaves-party-as-jeremy-corbyn-says-quitters-were-elected-on-his-manifesto-1-4875902|archive-date=13 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCreagh was defeated at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]] by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate [[Imran Ahmad-Khan]].\n\n==== Brexit ====\n\nCreagh supported Remain in the [[Campaigning in the United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016|EU referendum]], a move that was seen at odds with her Leave-voting constituency.<ref name=\"Yorkshire Evening Post\"/> Creagh voted against the [[United Kingdom invocation of Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union|triggering of Article 50]] in February 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/wakefield-mp-mary-creagh-votes-against-brexit-bill-but-article-50-could-be-triggered-within-weeks-after-parliament-passes-it-through-1-8380151|title=Wakefield MP Mary Creagh votes against Brexit bill but article 50 could be triggered within weeks after parliament passes it through|last=|first=|date=9 February 2017|website=Wakefield Express|language=|accessdate=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424003727/http://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/wakefield-mp-mary-creagh-votes-against-brexit-bill-but-article-50-could-be-triggered-within-weeks-after-parliament-passes-it-through-1-8380151|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She has stated that \u2018blue passports' were \u201cnot worth \u00a350 billion and crashing the economy\u201d.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-42443253 |title='Iconic' blue British passport to return after Brexit \u2013 BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723161946/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-42443253 |archive-date=23 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> She has also stated that the UK leaving the EU would be bad for the planet, and \u201cmore than the harm\u201d which would be done by [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Bates |first=Liz |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/environment/global-warming/news/95604/excl-brexit-bigger-threat-planet-donald-trump-says-top |title=EXCL Brexit a bigger threat to planet than Donald Trump, says top Labour MP |publisher=PoliticsHome.com |date= |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726201628/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/environment/global-warming/news/95604/excl-brexit-bigger-threat-planet-donald-trump-says-top |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Creagh's security has been stepped up after property damage and a \"credible threat\" in relation to her opposition to Brexit. In 2017, a constituent was jailed for harassment after sending Creagh far right inflenced material.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/mp-mary-creagh-wears-mobile-attack-alarms-in-the-office-and-outside-over-safety-fears-1-9628215|title=MP Mary Creagh 'wears mobile attack alarms in the office and outside' over safety fears|last=Bates|first=Liz|date=4 March 2018|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=Wakefield Express|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112103157/https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/mp-mary-creagh-wears-mobile-attack-alarms-in-the-office-and-outside-over-safety-fears-1-9628215|archive-date=12 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2019, she called on the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] to express \"full-throated support\" for a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|second EU referendum]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/peoples-vote-rally-hilary-benn-urges-labour-to-back-second-referendum-11747131 |title=People's Vote rally: Hilary Benn urges Labour to back second referendum &#124; Politics News &#124; Sky News |publisher=News.sky.com |date=2019-06-24 |accessdate=2019-10-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191011162720/https://news.sky.com/story/peoples-vote-rally-hilary-benn-urges-labour-to-back-second-referendum-11747131 |archive-date=11 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCreagh married Adrian Pulham in 2001. They have a son and a daughter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marycreagh.co.uk/index.php?id=538 |title=Mary Has A New Baby |date=10 October 2007 |publisher=Mary Creagh official website |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.marycreagh.co.uk/index.php?id=538 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She is a keen cyclist.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://totalpolitics.com/articles/interview/moving-through-gears-mary-creagh-interview|title=\nMoving through the gears: Mary Creagh interview|last=Chakelian|first=Anoosh|date=27 March 2014|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=Total Politics}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.marycreagh.co.uk/ Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150706075534/http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/24103/Mary-CREAGH Bio at ''Debrett's People of Today'']\n*{{UK MP links|parliament=mary-creagh/1579|hansard=<!--ms-mary-creagh-->|hansardcurr=4765 |guardian=8855/mary-creagh|publicwhip=Mary_Creagh|theywork=mary_creagh|record=1042 |bbc=36019.stm|journalisted=mary-creagh}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Hinchliffe]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Wakefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Wakefield]]|years=2005\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Imran Ahmad-Khan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hilary Benn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]|years=2010\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Maria Eagle]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Maria Eagle]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]]|years=2013\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael Dugher]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Diane Abbott]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Miliband Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{2015 Labour Party leadership election}}\n{{Yorkshire and the Humber Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Creagh, Mary}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of Cranfield University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Pembroke College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:British people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Islington]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:People from Coventry]]\n[[Category:Politics of Wakefield]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Labour politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{pp|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = [[Chartered Institute of Linguists|FCIL]]\n| name = Mary Creagh\n| caption = Creagh in 2017\n| image = Official portrait of Mary Creagh crop 2.jpg\n| office = Chair of the [[Environmental Audit Select Committee]]\n| term_start = 10 February 2016\n| term_end = 6 November 2019\n| predecessor = [[Huw Irranca-Davies]]\n| successor = [[Philip Dunne (Ludlow MP)|Philip Dunne]]\n| module = {{Collapsed infobox section begin |[[Shadow Cabinet]] positions\n |titlestyle     = border:1px dashed lightgrey}}{{Infobox officeholder\n |embed          = yes\n | office1 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]]\n | leader1 = [[Ed Miliband]]<br />[[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n | 1blankname1 = Shadowing\n | 1namedata1 = [[Justine Greening]]\n | term_start1 = 5 November 2014\n | term_end1 = 12 September 2015\n | predecessor1 = [[Jim Murphy]]\n | successor1 = [[Diane Abbott]]\n | office2 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]]\n | leader2 = [[Ed Miliband]]\n | 1blankname2 = Shadowing\n | 1namedata2 = [[Patrick McLoughlin]]\n | term_start2 = 7 October 2013\n | term_end2 = 5 November 2014\n | predecessor2 = [[Maria Eagle]]\n | successor2 = [[Michael Dugher]]\n | office3 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]\n | leader3 = [[Ed Miliband]]\n | 1blankname3 = Shadowing\n | 1namedata3 = [[Caroline Spelman]]<br />[[Owen Paterson]]\n | term_start3 = 8 October 2010\n | term_end3 = 7 October 2013\n | predecessor3 = [[Hilary Benn]]\n | successor3 = [[Maria Eagle]]\n {{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n| office4 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Wakefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Wakefield]]\n| term_start4 = 5 May 2005\n| term_end4 = 6 November 2019\n| predecessor4 = [[David Hinchliffe]]\n| successor4 = [[Imran Ahmad-Khan]]\n| module = {{Collapsed infobox section begin |[[Islington London Borough Council]] positions\n |titlestyle     = border:1px dashed lightgrey}}{{Infobox officeholder\n |embed          = yes\n | office5 = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] Group Leader<br />on [[Islington London Borough Council]]\n | term_start5 = 2000\n | term_end5 = 2004\n | predecessor5 = Derek Sawyer\n | successor5 = [[Catherine West]]\n | office6 = [[Councillor#United Kingdom|Councillor]] for [[Islington London Borough Council]]\n | 1blankname6 = [[Wards of the United Kingdom|Ward]]\n | 1namedata6 = Highbury West\n | term_start6 = 7 May 1998\n | term_end6 = 5 May 2005\n | successor6 = Theresa Debono\n {{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n| birth_name = Mary Helen Creagh\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|12|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Coventry]], [[Warwickshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = Adrian Pulham\n| children = 1 daughter<br />1 son\n| alma_mater = [[Pembroke College, Oxford]]<br />[[London School of Economics]]\n| website = [http://www.marycreagh.co.uk Official website]\n}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Mary Helen Creagh''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|FCIL}} (born 2 December 1967) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician who represented [[Wakefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Wakefield]] as a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) from [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]] until [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]].\n\nIn 2010, Creagh was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]],<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title = The shadow cabinet in full|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/oct/08/the-shadow-cabinet-in-full|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 4 June 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150605021336/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/oct/08/the-shadow-cabinet-in-full|archive-date = 5 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> before becoming [[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]] in 2013.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title = Labour frontbench reshuffle sees Blairites out and 'brightest of 2010 intake' promoted|url = https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/labour-frontbench-reshuffle-sees-blairites-2348748|accessdate = 4 June 2015|first = Jason|last = Beattie|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150605040853/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/labour-frontbench-reshuffle-sees-blairites-2348748|archive-date = 5 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> In November 2014 she was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]].<ref name=\"bbc-20141105\" />\n\nOn 14 May 2015, Creagh announced she would run for [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]] in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|leadership election]] resulting from [[Ed Miliband]]'s resignation,<ref>{{Cite news|title = Labour leadership: Mary Creagh enters race|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-32742236|website = BBC News|accessdate = 4 June 2015|date = 14 May 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150604031112/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-32742236|archive-date = 4 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> although she later withdrew her candidacy.\n\nShe resigned from the front bench following the election as Labour leader of [[Jeremy Corbyn]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nOf Irish descent, Creagh was born in [[Coventry]],<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://books.google.com/?id=YnAmle9e7AMC&pg=PA963&dq=%22mary+creagh%22+coventry#v=onepage&q=%22mary%20creagh%22%20coventry&f=false\n |author=Robert Waller and Byron Criddle \n |title=The Almanac of British Politics \n |year=2007 \n |publisher=[[Routledge]] \n |work=[[Taylor & Francis]] \n |edition=8 \n |isbn=978-0-203-94691-6 \n |df= \n}}{{dead link|date=August 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> where her father was a car factory worker and her mother a primary school teacher.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} She was educated at the [[Bishop Ullathorne Roman Catholic School|Bishop Ullathorne]] [[Comprehensive School]] in Coventry and read [[Modern Languages]] at [[Pembroke College, Oxford]], graduating as [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA (Oxon)]].<ref>{{cite news\n |newspaper=[[Coventry Telegraph]] \n |url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/cov-kid-mary-creagh-lands-3055134 \n |author=Mary Griffin \n |title=Cov kid Mary Creagh lands key Labour shadow cabinet role \n |date=12 October 2010 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/cov-kid-mary-creagh-lands-3055134 \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> After pursuing European Studies at the [[London School of Economics]] ([[PhD]]),<ref>[http://www.pressreader.com/uk/yorkshire-post/20150311/281943131354556/TextView www.pressreader.com: Dr Mary Creagh MP]</ref> she is a fluent [[French language|French]] and [[Italian language|Italian]] speaker.\n\t\nCreagh worked in [[Brussels]] for four years, first as an [[intern]] at the [[European Parliament]] and then for the [[European Youth Forum]]. She [[Lecturer|lectured]] in entrepreneurship at the [[Cranfield University|Cranfield School of Management]] and served for seven years as a [[Trustee]] of [[Rathbone (charity)|Rathbone]], a national charity.\n\n===Councillor in Islington===\nCreagh was elected as a [[Councillor]] for the [[London Borough of Islington]] in [[1998 Islington Council election|1998]], representing Highbury West ward (renamed Highbury in 2002), and served as the Labour Group Leader for five years during a period when the party was in opposition locally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://londondatastore-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/docs/LBCE_1998-5-7.pdf|title=London Borough Council Elections 7 May 1998|authors=Minors, Michael and Grenham, Dennis|publisher=Greater London Authority|accessdate=26 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008083524/http://londondatastore-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/docs/LBCE_1998-5-7.pdf|archive-date=8 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://files.datapress.com/london/dataset/council-elections-voters-2002/London-Borough-Council-Elections-2002.pdf|title=London Borough Council Elections 2 May 2002|authors=Minors, Michael and Grenham, Dennis|publisher=Greater London Authority|accessdate=26 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220105908/https://files.datapress.com/london/dataset/council-elections-voters-2002/London-Borough-Council-Elections-2002.pdf|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> During this time, she knocked on doors and ran a campaign office for future party leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]].<ref name=\"Yorkshire Evening Post\">{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/mary-creagh-i-want-to-bring-wakefield-out-of-leeds-s-shadow-and-into-the-future-1-9021472 |title=Mary Creagh: 'I want to bring Wakefield out of Leeds's shadow and into the future' |work=Yorkshire Evening Post |date=17 February 2018 |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726234826/https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/politics/mary-creagh-i-want-to-bring-wakefield-out-of-leeds-s-shadow-and-into-the-future-1-9021472 |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> She stood down from [[Islington London Borough Council|Islington Council]] in 2005 upon her election to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dathan|first1=Matt|title=Labour Leadership Race: Who is Mary Creagh?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/labour-leadership-race-who-is-mary-creagh-10251452.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=30 May 2015|location=London|date=14 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518003621/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/labour-leadership-race-who-is-mary-creagh-10251452.html|archive-date=18 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Creagh formally alleged [[cronyism]] in the appointment of the Islington Council [[chief executive]] by five [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] councillors thus triggering an investigation by the [[Standards Board for England]]. After the longest ever investigation by the Standards Board, her complaint was rejected. Creagh was criticised by the [[tribunal]] as being \"heavily influenced by her political motives\" and that she was an \"insensitive witness, lacking in balanced judgment and one who was prepared to make assumptions about honesty and integrity of others without any proper basis\".<ref name=\"Guardian Media Group\">{{cite news|last1=Weaver|first1=Matt|title=Council leader cleared of cronyism charge|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2006/jan/05/localgovernment.politics1|accessdate=30 May 2015|publisher=Guardian Media Group|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530182251/http://www.theguardian.com/society/2006/jan/05/localgovernment.politics1|archive-date=30 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> However, Creagh defended herself saying she \"blew the whistle because I believed the Liberal Democrats were not meeting the standards we expect from people in public office. I invite people to look at my evidence and draw their own conclusions\".<ref name=\"Guardian Media Group\"/>\n\nThe Liberal Democrat councillors involved lost their seats at the 2006 elections, their [[Political party|party]] also lost control of the Council.<ref>{{cite news|title=Election 2006: Islington|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/vote2006/locals/html/au.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924162150/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/vote2006/locals/html/au.stm|archive-date=24 September 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n\n=== Backbencher and early posts: 2005\u20132010 ===\n[[File:Mary Creagh, 2016 Labour Party Conference.jpg|upright|thumb|Creagh speaking at a 2016 Labour Party Conference fringe meeting]]\nCreagh succeeded the retiring [[David Hinchliffe]] as MP for Wakefield. She won the seat in [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Election 2005: Wakefield|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/vote2005/html/602.stm|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051221064526/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/vote2005/html/602.stm|archive-date=21 December 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> with a majority of 5,154, and held the seat \u2013 altered by boundary changes \u2013 with a majority of 1,613 [[2010 United Kingdom general election|five years later]]. She made her [[maiden speech]] in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]] on 25 May 2005 using the occasion to raise issues of poverty in her constituency. She also mentioned locally-born sculptor [[Barbara Hepworth]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm050525/debtext/50525-29.htm#50525-29_spnew0 \n |title=Maiden speech in Hansard \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm050525/debtext/50525-29.htm \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\nShe was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Andy Burnham]], [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport]], from 2006 until June 2009, when she was appointed as an assistant government whip in the Department of Health.<ref name=progress-20130228/>\n\nShe was a member of the [[Human Rights]] [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|Select committee]] from 2005 until 2007. From 2007 to 2009, she was Chair of the Labour Movement for Europe,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://labourmovement.eu/ |title=www.labourmovement.eu |access-date=26 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226040913/http://labourmovement.eu/ |archive-date=26 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> succeeding [[Chris Bryant]] MP and being succeeded by [[Richard Corbett]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]. She is a member of the [[Labour Friends of Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-s-pro-israel-mps-face-wipe-out-1.436505|title=Labour's pro-Israel MPs face wipe-out|publisher=The Jewish Chronicle|date=20 April 2017|access-date=10 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730110854/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-s-pro-israel-mps-face-wipe-out-1.436505|archive-date=30 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn Labour leadership elections, she backed [[Gordon Brown]] in 2007<ref>{{cite news|title=Who's backing Gordon Brown? |publisher=theguardian.com |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/may/17/labourleadership.labour1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2007/may/17/labourleadership.labour1 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |location=London |date=17 May 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[David Miliband]] in May 2010.<ref name=progress-20130228>{{cite web |url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2013/02/28/mary-mary/ |title=Mary, Mary? |publisher=Progress |date=28 February 2013 |accessdate=23 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150615002728/http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2013/02/28/mary-mary/ |archive-date=15 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter entering the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], Creagh campaigned successfully on a number of issues. In 2005, she introduced a Children's Food Bill which sought to introduce minimum nutritional standards for all school meals and take fizzy drinks and sugary snacks out of school vending machines. Both of these measures were accepted by the government and became law under the [[Education and Inspections Act 2006]].<ref>{{cite web\n |title=The Education and Inspections Bill 2006 \n |url=http://www.standards.dfes.gov.uk/new/published/edubill \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.standards.dfes.gov.uk/new/published/edubill \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> In 2006, Creagh launched a campaign aimed at preventing [[scalding]] injuries in the home. She brought together medical experts, campaign groups and victims of scalding injuries to lobby the government to change the building regulations to prevent people being severely scalded by hot water. The coalition pressured the government to make the fitting of a water temperature regulating device, such as a [[thermostatic mixing valve]] (TMV), compulsory in new bathrooms in England. In 2009, after a three-year \"Hot Water Burns Like Fire\" campaign, the Labour government confirmed TMVs were to be a standard fitment in all new bathrooms from April 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotwaterburnslikefire.org.uk/ |title=Hot Water Burns Like Fire |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.hotwaterburnslikefire.org.uk/ |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release\n |url=http://www.politics.co.uk/opinion-formers/press-releases/health/beama-mps-welcome-scalding-campaign-success-$1310419$366174.htm \n |title=BEAMA: MPs welcome scalding campaign success \n |date=10 July 2009 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.politics.co.uk/opinion-formers/press-releases/health/beama-mps-welcome-scalding-campaign-success-%241310419%24366174.htm \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> In 2009, as Vice Chair of the [[All-Party Parliamentary Group]] for the Prevention of Genocide and Other Crimes Against Humanity, Creagh called on Justice Secretary [[Jack Straw]] to tighten British Law so people accused of genocide could be prosecuted in the [[Law of the United Kingdom|UK]]. She said there was an \"impunity gap\" which allowed people accused of terrible crimes in places like [[Rwanda]] and [[Bosnia]] to escape justice and live freely in Britain.<ref>{{cite news\n |title=UK plans new powers on genocide \n |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8139045.stm \n |publisher=BBC News \n |date=7 July 2009 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8139045.stm \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> As a result of this, the government agreed to amend the [[Coroners and Justice Act 2009|Coroner's and Justice Bill]] to tighten the [[United Kingdom legislation|law]] so anyone suspected of [[war crimes]] anywhere throughout the world since 1991 and resident in the UK could be prosecuted in [[Courts of the United Kingdom|UK courts]].<ref>{{cite news\n |publisher=[[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Justice]] \n |title=Jack Straw to strengthen law title \n |date=7 July 2009 \n |url=http://www.justice.gov.uk/news/newsrelease070709b.htm \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.justice.gov.uk/news/newsrelease070709b.htm \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\n=== Shadow Cabinet: 2010\u20132015 ===\nOn 8 October 2010, Creagh was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In February 2011 she secured a House of Commons debate<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Public Forest Estate (England) debate \n |publisher=[[Hansard]] \n |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110202/debtext/110202-0003.htm#11020248002385 \n |date=2 February 2011 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110202/debtext/110202-0003.htm \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> on the government\u2019s plans to sell off 85% of [[Forestry in the United Kingdom|public forestry]]. The government subsequently abandoned these plans,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-12488847 |title=Forest sale axed |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |date=16 February 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-12488847 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> it having become clear that the public \"were not happy with the proposals\".<ref>{{cite web\n |publisher=[[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|DEFRA]] \n |title=The future of forestry in England \n |url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2011/02/17/futureforestry/ \n |date=17 February 2011 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2011/02/17/futureforestry/ \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> In 2011, Creagh criticised the decision by the [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]] to cut [[Flood control|flood defence]] spending in real terms by 32%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/house_of_commons/newsid_9392000/9392060.stm |date=9 February 2011 |title=Urgent Question: Flood defences |publisher=BBC News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/house_of_commons/newsid_9392000/9392060.stm |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In addition to her involvement in campaigns calling for the banning of wild animals performing in [[circus]]es,<ref>{{cite news|title=Labour calls for ban on wild animals in circuses |date=19 May 2011 |publisher=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/house_of_commons/newsid_9490000/9490875.stm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/house_of_commons/newsid_9490000/9490875.stm |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> she has opposed the government's policy of badger culling, claiming it was \"anti-science\" and that the option of vaccination should be explored.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Creagh|first1=Mary|title=In pursuing the badger cull, the government is being anti-science|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/aug/26/badger-cull-government-anti-science|website=Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611014757/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/aug/26/badger-cull-government-anti-science|archive-date=11 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[Labour Party (UK) Conference|Labour Party's Annual Conference]] in September 2011, Creagh launched the campaign ''Back the Apple''.<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.youtube.com/watch?v=x2DluFoQlak|title=Back the Apple|publisher=[[YouTube]]|work=[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]|date=24 September 2011|access-date=19 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204132223/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x2DluFoQlak|archive-date=4 December 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> with [[Unite the Union]]. The campaign opposes the government\u2019s plan to abolish the [[Agricultural Wages Board]]<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/food-farm/farm-manage/wages/ \n |title=Agricultural employment and wages \n |publisher=DAFTA \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.defra.gov.uk/food-farm/farm-manage/wages/ \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> which sets wages and conditions for thousands of agricultural workers.\n\nIn 2013, Creagh was appointed Shadow Secretary of State for Transport.<ref name=\":1\" /> On 24 March 2014 she and [[Jamie Hanley]] opposed the train fares price increases in [[New Pudsey railway station|New Pudsey]] proposed by [[Patrick McLoughlin]]. The opposition spread throughout 18 [[West Yorkshire]] stations, forcing McLoughlin to scrap the plan.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Telegraph & Argus]] |date=24 March 2014 |accessdate=30 March 2014 |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/11096418.Mary_Creagh_joins_transport_fight_at_New_Pudsey/?ref=var_0 |title=Mary Creagh joins transport fight at New Pudsey |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/11096418.Mary_Creagh_joins_transport_fight_at_New_Pudsey/?ref=var_0 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The same day she took part in the minibus opening ceremony which was hosted by [[Colchester|Colchester Community Volunteer Service]]<ref>{{cite news\n |date=24 March 2014 \n |accessdate=30 March 2014 \n |url=http://www.essexcountystandard.co.uk/news/ecsnews/11097731.All_aboard_the_new_bus_/ \n |title=CCVS celebrates as sixth bus takes to the road \n |author=Wendy Brading \n |newspaper=[[Essex County Standard]] \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.essexcountystandard.co.uk/news/ecsnews/11097731.All_aboard_the_new_bus_/ \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> and two days later accused the government of donating their time into privatising [[East Coast Main Line]] instead of worrying about high fare prices.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/blighty/2014/03/rail-privatisation \n |publisher=The Economist \n |title=Fractious tracks \n |date=26 March 2014 \n |accessdate=30 March 2014 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/https://www.economist.com/blogs/blighty/2014/03/rail-privatisation \n |archivedate=30 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, she became [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]].<ref name=\"bbc-20141105\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29918950 |title=Labour reshuffle: Dugher and Powell promoted by Ed Miliband |publisher=BBC |date=5 November 2014 |accessdate=30 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627120659/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29918950 |archive-date=27 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== Labour leadership candidate ====\nOn 14 May 2015, Creagh announced her candidacy for [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]], after [[Ed Miliband]]'s resignation following the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} On 12 June, Creagh announced that she was withdrawing from the leadership contest. At the time of her announcement, she had secured about 10 nominations from Labour MPs, fewer than any of the other remaining candidates and well short of the 35 required to take part in the final ballot.<ref name=\"BBC News 12 June 2015\">{{cite news | title= Mary Creagh pulls out of Labour leadership race | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-33117505 | author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | date= 12 June 2015 | website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= 12 June 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150614044929/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-33117505 | archive-date= 14 June 2015 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Return to the backbenches: 2015\u20132019===\nAfter the election of Jeremy Corbyn as Labour leader in September 2015, Creagh resigned from the front bench.<ref>{{cite web |title=Andy Burnham and John McDonnell get top jobs in Corbyn's Shadow Cabinet |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=14 September 2015 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/11862774/andy-burnham-shadow-home-secretary-jeremy-corbyn-cabinet.html |accessdate=14 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914222013/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/11862774/andy-burnham-shadow-home-secretary-jeremy-corbyn-cabinet.html |archive-date=14 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> She supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=21 July 2016|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715214543/https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], Creagh was reported as writing to constituents to say that her team had been \u201cspeaking to people in your street\u201d who had told them they had \u201cmore confidence in Theresa May as Prime Minister than Jeremy Corbyn,\u201d predicted a large Tory majority and called for a vote for them as individuals while promising to \u201cwork for a Labour Party that can once again regain your confidence.\u201d The letter was similar to ones sent by [[Joan Ryan]] and [[Gavin Shuker]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/h-lead-labour-friends-israel-chair-among-mps-losing-no-confidence-votes|title=Labour Friends of Israel chair Joan Ryan and Luton South's Gavin Shuker lose no confidence votes|last=Chacko|first=Ben|date=7 September 2018|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=Morning Star|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907202652/https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/h-lead-labour-friends-israel-chair-among-mps-losing-no-confidence-votes|archive-date=7 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n \nOn the BBC programme ''[[Newsnight]]'' (1 December 2015) Creagh argued in favour of military action in Syria, stating: \"ISIL pose a clear threat to Britain\", \"it makes no sense to turn our planes back at the Syrian border\" and \"we must act to keep our country safe\"<ref name=\"BBC Newsnight 01 December 2015\">{{cite news | title= Mary Creagh Newsnight appearance | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06r2q66 | date= 1 December 2015 | publisher= BBC | accessdate= 1 December 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151207183515/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06r2q66 | archive-date= 7 December 2015 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Creagh became chair of the [[Environmental Audit Select Committee|Environmental Audit Committee]].\n\nIn November 2018, Creagh expressed sympathy for [[Angela Smith (South Yorkshire politician)|Angela Smith]] after Smith's [[Constituency Labour Party]] passed a vote of no confidence in her.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/99939/labour-mp-hits-out-hard-left-cabal-after-losing|title=Labour MP hits out at 'hard-left cabal' after losing vote of confidence|last=Schofield|first=Kevin|date=17 November 2018|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=Politics Home|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181117114939/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/99939/labour-mp-hits-out-hard-left-cabal-after-losing|archive-date=17 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2019, Creagh was invited to join the [[Change UK]] breakaway of Labour MPs, but declined.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/eighth-labour-mp-leaves-party-as-jeremy-corbyn-says-quitters-were-elected-on-his-manifesto-1-4875902|title=Eighth Labour MP leaves party as Jeremy Corbyn says quitters were elected on his manifesto|last=Gourtsoyannis|first=Paris|date=20 February 2019|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=The Scotsman|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190613021625/https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/eighth-labour-mp-leaves-party-as-jeremy-corbyn-says-quitters-were-elected-on-his-manifesto-1-4875902|archive-date=13 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCreagh was defeated at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]] by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate [[Imran Ahmad-Khan]].\n\n==== Brexit ====\n\nCreagh supported Remain in the [[Campaigning in the United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016|EU referendum]], a move that was seen at odds with her Leave-voting constituency.<ref name=\"Yorkshire Evening Post\"/> Creagh voted against the [[United Kingdom invocation of Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union|triggering of Article 50]] in February 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/wakefield-mp-mary-creagh-votes-against-brexit-bill-but-article-50-could-be-triggered-within-weeks-after-parliament-passes-it-through-1-8380151|title=Wakefield MP Mary Creagh votes against Brexit bill but article 50 could be triggered within weeks after parliament passes it through|last=|first=|date=9 February 2017|website=Wakefield Express|language=|accessdate=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424003727/http://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/wakefield-mp-mary-creagh-votes-against-brexit-bill-but-article-50-could-be-triggered-within-weeks-after-parliament-passes-it-through-1-8380151|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She has stated that \u2018blue passports' were \u201cnot worth \u00a350 billion and crashing the economy\u201d.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-42443253 |title='Iconic' blue British passport to return after Brexit \u2013 BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723161946/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-42443253 |archive-date=23 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> She has also stated that the UK leaving the EU would be bad for the planet, and \u201cmore than the harm\u201d which would be done by [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Bates |first=Liz |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/environment/global-warming/news/95604/excl-brexit-bigger-threat-planet-donald-trump-says-top |title=EXCL Brexit a bigger threat to planet than Donald Trump, says top Labour MP |publisher=PoliticsHome.com |date= |accessdate=26 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726201628/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/environment/global-warming/news/95604/excl-brexit-bigger-threat-planet-donald-trump-says-top |archive-date=26 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Creagh's security has been stepped up after property damage and a \"credible threat\" in relation to her opposition to Brexit. In 2017, a constituent was jailed for harassment after sending Creagh far right inflenced material.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/mp-mary-creagh-wears-mobile-attack-alarms-in-the-office-and-outside-over-safety-fears-1-9628215|title=MP Mary Creagh 'wears mobile attack alarms in the office and outside' over safety fears|last=Bates|first=Liz|date=4 March 2018|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=Wakefield Express|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112103157/https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/politics/mp-mary-creagh-wears-mobile-attack-alarms-in-the-office-and-outside-over-safety-fears-1-9628215|archive-date=12 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2019, she called on the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] to express \"full-throated support\" for a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|second EU referendum]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/peoples-vote-rally-hilary-benn-urges-labour-to-back-second-referendum-11747131 |title=People's Vote rally: Hilary Benn urges Labour to back second referendum &#124; Politics News &#124; Sky News |publisher=News.sky.com |date=2019-06-24 |accessdate=2019-10-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191011162720/https://news.sky.com/story/peoples-vote-rally-hilary-benn-urges-labour-to-back-second-referendum-11747131 |archive-date=11 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCreagh married Adrian Pulham in 2001. They have a son and a daughter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marycreagh.co.uk/index.php?id=538 |title=Mary Has A New Baby |date=10 October 2007 |publisher=Mary Creagh official website |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.marycreagh.co.uk/index.php?id=538 |archivedate=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She is a keen cyclist.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://totalpolitics.com/articles/interview/moving-through-gears-mary-creagh-interview|title=\nMoving through the gears: Mary Creagh interview|last=Chakelian|first=Anoosh|date=27 March 2014|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=Total Politics}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.marycreagh.co.uk/ Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150706075534/http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/24103/Mary-CREAGH Bio at ''Debrett's People of Today'']\n*{{UK MP links|parliament=mary-creagh/1579|hansard=<!--ms-mary-creagh-->|hansardcurr=4765 |guardian=8855/mary-creagh|publicwhip=Mary_Creagh|theywork=mary_creagh|record=1042 |bbc=36019.stm|journalisted=mary-creagh}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Hinchliffe]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Wakefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Wakefield]]|years=2005\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Imran Ahmad-Khan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hilary Benn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]|years=2010\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Maria Eagle]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Maria Eagle]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Transport]]|years=2013\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael Dugher]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Diane Abbott]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Miliband Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{2015 Labour Party leadership election}}\n{