{"title_page": "Geoffrey Cox (British politician)", "text_new": "{{COI|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Geoffrey Cox\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|QC}} [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Geoffrey Cox QC MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption =\n| office = [[Attorney General for England and Wales]]<br />[[Advocate General for Northern Ireland]]\n| primeminister = [[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 9 July 2018\n| term_end = 13 February 2020\n| predecessor = [[Jeremy Wright]]\n| successor = [[Suella Braverman]]\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Torridge and West Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|Torridge and West Devon]]\n| parliament1 = \n| term_start1 = 5 May 2005\n| term_end1 =\n| majority1 = 24,992 (41.8%)\n| predecessor1 = [[John Burnett, Baron Burnett|John Burnett]]\n| successor1 =\n|birth_name=Charles Geoffrey Cox\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1960|04|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Wroughton]], [[Wiltshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = Jeanie Cox\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations = \n| children = 3\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Downing College, Cambridge]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = {{URL|www.geoffreycox.co.uk}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Charles Geoffrey Cox''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|QC}}<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59418 |date=13 May 2010 |page=8741}}</ref> (born 30 April 1960) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician and [[barrister]] serving as [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Torridge and West Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|Torridge and West Devon]] since the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]]. Cox worked as a barrister from 1982 onwards and was appointed a [[Queen's Counsel]] in 2003, two years before his election to Parliament. On 9 July 2018, he was appointed [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] and gave up private practice; prior to this he had been the highest earning MP in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|title=The richest MPs in Britain based on income|url= http://uk.businessinsider.com/the-richest-mp-in-terms-of-second-incomes-2017-8/#3-kenneth-clarke-conservative-274800-mostly-from-his-autobiography-deal-11|work=Business Insider|accessdate=16 August 2018|date=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nCharles Geoffrey Cox was born in [[Wroughton]], [[Wiltshire]] on 30 April 1960 to Michael (a Royal Artillery Officer) and Diane Cox. He was educated at [[King's College, Taunton]], an [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent school]] in Somerset. He studied law and classics at [[Downing College, Cambridge]].<ref name=UKWW>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-2000219?rskey=ubli0k&result=3|publisher=UK Who's Who|accessdate=25 September 2019|title=Cox, Rt Hon. (Charles) Geoffrey}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/geoffrey-cox-profile-from-back-benches-to-eye-of-the-storm-p53xhdhbz |title=Geoffrey Cox profile: from back benches to eye of the storm |work=The Times |location= London |date=13 March 2019 |last=Zeffman |first=Henry}}{{subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\n\n[[Called to the Bar]] at the [[Middle Temple]] in 1982, Cox started practice as a barrister; in 1992 he co-founded Thomas More Chambers, serving as its Head of Chambers. He was appointed [[Queen's Counsel]] in 2003.<ref name=geof>{{cite web|url=http://www.thomasmore.co.uk/members/geoffrey_cox_qc |title=Thomas More Chambers: Geoffrey Cox QC |accessdate=24 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129222634/http://www.thomasmore.co.uk/members/geoffrey_cox_qc |archivedate=29 November 2014  }}</ref>\n\nFor part of his career as a barrister, Cox was Standing Counsel to the government of the [[Indian Ocean]] island nation of [[Mauritius]]. His cases have included \"civil fraud and asset recovery, commercial, human rights, defamation, and judicial review actions\". He has frequently appeared as leading counsel in the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]] or the [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council|Privy Council]], and he was increasingly instructed to lead in commercial actions and arbitrations overseas, appearing in the [[Dubai International Financial Centre|DIFC]], Mauritius and the [[Cayman Islands]].<ref name=geof/>\n\nHis criminal cases have included the [[Jubilee line corruption trial]]; representing Virendra Rastogi the owner of [[RBG Resources]];<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/fraudster-tycoon-with-mayfair-flat-is-given-5-million-legal-aid-7499116.html |title=Fraudster tycoon with Mayfair flat is given \u00a35 million legal aid |work=London Evening Standard |date=2 March 2012 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> and successfully defending a member of the [[Queen's Lancashire Regiment]] who had been accused of [[war crime]]s related to the [[death of Baha Mousa]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Williams |first=A.T. |date=18 October 2012 |title=A Very British Killing |url=https://books.google.com/?id=a19QjWd5f68C&pg=PA200&lpg=PA200&dq=geoffrey+cox+donald+payne#v=onepage&q=geoffrey%20cox%20donald%20payne&f=false |publisher=Jonathan Cape |page=200 |isbn=978-0224096881}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Cox successfully defended the former Premier (and current  Speaker of the Legislative Assembly) of the Cayman Islands, [[McKeeva Bush]], on charges of corruption and misuse of office.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.compasscayman.com/caycompass/2014/10/10/Courtroom-theater-draws-crowds/|title=Courtroom theater draws crowds|author=James Whittaker|work=Cayman Compass|date=10 October 2014|accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref> In March 2015, Cox successfully defended the deputy Editor of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', [[Geoff Webster]], in a trial of four journalists resulting from [[Operation Elveden]].<ref name=beeeb>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-31998319|title=Sun journalist's lawyer queries use of 'vague' law|work=BBC News|date=21 March 2015|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> The jury had to decide at what point the behaviour of those on trial could be considered a criminal rather than a serious disciplinary matter; even the lawyers found this difficult to define.<ref name=lisa>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/mar/20/acquittal-four-senior-sun-journalists-blow-cps |title=Acquittal of four senior Sun journalists seen as blow to CPS |work=The Guardian |location= London |first=Lisa |last=O'Carroll|date=20 March 2015|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> Cox subsequently publicly criticised the vagueness of the law, and its disproportionate use that had led to the prosecution.<ref name=beeeb/>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n[[File:Geoffrey Cox MP hosting Lamerton Hunt 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Cox hosting a lawn meet of the [[Lamerton]] Foxhounds, 2014]]\nCox was first selected to stand for Parliament in 2000 by the Torridge and West Devon Conservatives. In the following [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], he came second to incumbent [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[John Burnett, Baron Burnett|John Burnett]] by 1,194 votes.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/england/4519145.stm |title=One change in Devon political map |publisher=BBC News|date=6 May 2005|accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/results_constituencies/constituencies/191.stm|title=Devon West & Torridge|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2001 election, Cox was reselected. Burnett announced in 2003 that he would not contest the seat again, and at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] Cox defeated the new Liberal Democrat candidate, [[David Walter (British journalist and politician)|David Walter]], gaining a majority of 3,236.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/vote2005/html/191.stm|title=Result: Devon West & Torridge|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=25 September 2019|date=6 May 2005}}</ref> Cox made his [[maiden speech]] in the House of Commons on 28 June 2005.\n\nCox was re-elected as MP for Torridge and West Devon at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] with an increased majority of 18,403 votes (32.5%).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14001000#election2015-logo|title=Devon West & Torridge|accessdate=25 September 2019|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> This majority increased by over 2,000 votes at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 election]] to 20,686 (34.7%).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14001000|title=Devon West & Torridge|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, it was reported he had a number of office expense claims for items, such as a 49p pint of milk, rejected by the Commons authorities. He was criticised for this as at the time Cox was Britain's highest-paid MP. In response, Cox said that his staff had been unaware of a recent change in the rules for office expenses, which no longer permitted office hospitality items such as tea, coffee or milk to be claimed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Geoffrey Cox: Tory MP has expenses claim for 49p pint of milk rejected by Commons |first=Andy |last=McSmith |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/geoffrey-cox-tory-mp-has-expenses-claim-for-49p-pint-of-milk-rejected-by-commons-a6813131.html |work=The Independent |location= London |accessdate=9 September 2018|date=14 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Cox was one of 72 MPs who were themselves landlords who derived an income from a property and who backed the Conservative Government in voting down an amendment in Parliament on rental homes being \"fit for human habitation\". The Government argued that the law already provided more effective remedies for tenants to report homes in bad repair to local authorities who then had a statutory duty to inspect them and to take action against the landlord, and that the previous Labour Government had for the same reason rejected the proposal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tories vote down law requiring landlords make their homes fit for human habitation |first=Jon |last=Stone |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tories-vote-down-law-requiring-landlords-make-their-homes-fit-for-human-habitation-a6809691.html |work=The Independent |location= London |accessdate=9 September 2018 |date=13 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Cox told the House of Commons that he had concluded, after examining the published renegotiation proposals, that the case for leaving the EU was now overwhelming and that he would vote to do so in the forthcoming [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geoffreycox.co.uk/content/eu-renegotiation-0|title=EU Renegotiation|publisher=Personal website|accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July 2018, Cox was appointed to the Cabinet as Her Majesty's Attorney General for England and Wales and Advocate General for Northern Ireland.\n\nIn the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] he has sat on the [[Department for the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]] [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|Select committee]], the Committee on Standards and the Committee on Privileges.<ref name=parliamentbiocox>{{cite web|title=Geoffrey Cox|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/geoffrey-cox/1508|website=Parliament UK|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref> Cox resigned from the latter role in 2016 after registering more than \u00a3400,000 of outside earnings within the time limit. <ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/12188113/MPs-must-no-longer-police-themselves.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=9 March 2016|accessdate=25 September 2019 |title=MPs must no longer police themselves, says sleaze watchdog Lord Bew |last1=Malnick |first1=Edward |last2=Newell |first2=Claire}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2019 General Election, Geoffrey Cox was re-elected with 60.1% of the vote and a majority of 24,992 (41.8%).\n\n===Attorney General===\n\nOn 9 July 2018, [[Theresa May]] appointed Cox as [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] (the government's top law officer) taking over from [[Jeremy Wright]] following a [[Cabinet reshuffle]], prompted by the resignations of [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]] and [[Boris Johnson]].\n\nOn 1 December 2018, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' newspaper reported the leaked contents of a recent Geoffrey Cox letter to Cabinet Ministers detailing the Attorney General's legal advice on Theresa May's Brexit deal. The newspaper reported that his legal advice declared the Withdrawal agreement's backstop protocol would mean the UK being indefinitely locked into a customs union with the EU if future negotiations collapse and that the only way the UK could leave the Backstop would be the signing of a future trade deal which could take many years to complete. The former [[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|Brexit Secretary]] [[Dominic Raab]] and three serving Cabinet members confirmed the contents of the letter to the ''Sunday Times''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Shipman |title=Revealed: Brexit legal advice could sink Theresa May |url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/revealed-brexit-legal-advice-could-sink-theresa-may-r9wmh0v89 |work=The Sunday Times |location= London |date=2 December 2018 }}{{subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Theresa May placed Cox in charge of negotiating changes to the [[Northern Ireland backstop]] in the [[European Union|EU]] [[Brexit withdrawal agreement|withdrawal agreement]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47409659 |title=May's fate in the hands of the 'showman' |work=BBC News |last=Watt |first=Nicholas |date=28 February 2019 |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 September 2019, the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] ruled unanimously that Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]]'s [[2019 British prorogation controversy|prorogation of parliament]] was unlawful overturning the High Court's judgment, given by the Lord Chief Justice, in the government's favour. On the same day, minutes of a conference call between cabinet ministers (which included Cox) were leaked to [[Sky News]]. The minutes of the call, which took place after the prorogation had been approved by the Queen, detailed that Cox briefly told the cabinet at that time that in his view the prorogation was lawful and constitutional and that any accusations of unlawfulness \"were motivated by political considerations\". Cox's full advice to the Government has not been published.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/exclusive-pm-was-advised-by-attorney-general-suspension-was-lawful-11818599|title=Exclusive: PM was advised by attorney general suspension was 'lawful' |website=Sky News |access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> The next day Cox appeared in the House of Commons to answer an urgent question on the Government's legal advice and on the implications of the Supreme Court's decision. Cox rebutted calls for him to resign and criticisms of the Government's position, pointing out that senior and distinguished judges had agreed with the Government's view that the issue was not justiciable and chiding MPs for refusing to agree to a means of the UK leaving the EU while repeatedly preventing the House of Commons from dissolving for an election.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/quentin-letts-sketch-verbal-barrage-from-the-flawed-projector-plv0fx9c3{{paywall}}</ref>{{verification-inline|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn February 2020 Cox said the public is concerned about the creeping \"judicialisation of politics\" and said people were right to worry that unelected officials were taking decisions that ought to be taken by Parliament. He promised there would not be radical reforms. He stated his opposition to the highly politicised US selection process of [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] and suggested he preferred the Canadian system. Cox said  that \"there's a case for looking at how supreme court judges are appointed... There's a committee of the Canadian parliament that carries out interviews [of candidates].\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/12/geoffrey-cox-signals-would-accept-lead-role-review-judiciary]</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51474169]</ref>\n\nOn 13 February 2020, the ''[[Financial Times]]''{{'}}s Whitehall correspondent reported that Cox had been sacked as Attorney General.\n\n==Outside work whilst employed as an MP==\n\nCox has continued to practise as a Queen's Counsel whilst an MP.<ref name=geof/> According to ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', based on the declarations in the Register of Members' Interests, Cox's extra-parliamentary work was worth \u00a3820,867 in 2014, or 12 times his annual MP salary, whilst the total time on extra-parliamentary work that was registered in 2014 (although the register shows the hours were worked over 3 years) was 1,954 hours.<ref name=lyn>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/investigations/11428075/The-MPs-who-topped-up-their-salaries-with-1600-an-hour-second-jobs.html |title=The MPs who topped up their salaries with \u00a31,600-an-hour second jobs |first1=Lyndsey |last1=Telford |first2=Luke |last2=Heighton |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=22 February 2015 |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> According to the  Register as of 2 July 2018], his extra-parliamentary earnings in the 12 months from July 2017 to June 2018 were \u00a3487,043; the time expended totalled 1,070 hours, carried out over several years.<ref>{{cite web |title=House of Commons - The Register of Members' Financial Interests (2 July 2018: Cox, Mr Geoffrey ) |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmregmem/180702/cox_geoffrey.htm |website=publications.parliament.uk |language=English}}</ref>\n\nCox has previously defended his outside work, pointing out that MPs of all parties have practised as QCs over the years, and that the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] and [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor General]] are normally chosen from their ranks.<ref name=west/> He has argued that he has always been used to long hours, 70 and 80 hour weeks were quite normal at the Bar, and that the [[Committee on Standards in Public Life|Nolan report]] concluded that Parliament needed people with current experience of a wide range of professional and other backgrounds.<ref name=west>{{cite news |url= http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Experience-world-work-lost-Commons/story-19179766-detail/story.html |title=Experience of world of work must not be lost in Commons |work= Western Morning News |location=Plymouth |first=Geoffrey |last=Cox |date=4 June 2013 |accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the House of Commons [[Commons Select Committee on Standards|Standards Committee]]\u2014of which he was a member\u2014found that he had committed a serious breach of a House of Commons rule, designed to make transparent an MP's financial interests, after failing to register \u00a3400k of outside earnings (11 payments) for legal work within the permitted 28-day period. Cox registered the payments late, variously between two and seven months after the deadline; he said that he had omitted to prioritise the rule in the midst of an intense political and professional schedule. When first registering the payments, in September 2015, Cox drew attention to and apologised to the Registrar for his omission, referring himself to the [[Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards|Parliamentary Commissioner]], and stepped down from the Committee.\n\nThe Commissioner and the Committee accepted that the payments had not in fact given rise to any conflicts of interest, and that the failure to register the payments within 28 days had thus had no practical effect. [[Alistair Graham]], the former Chairman of the [[Committee on Standards in Public Life]], criticised the lack of punishment and called for a complete reform, while [[Martin Bell]] said the Committee on Standards had a long history of inflicting light punishment, which showed that the House was incapable of regulating itself.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/conservative-mps-expenses/12140118/Tory-MP-Geoffrey-Cox-will-only-have-to-apologise-after-failing-to-declare-hundreds-of-thousands-of-pounds.html |title=Tory MP Geoffrey Cox will only have to apologise after failing to declare hundreds of thousands of pounds |first=Laura |last=Hughes |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=4 February 2016 |accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July 2018, Cox gave up all private practice upon his appointment as Attorney General.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-attorney-general-appointed|title= New Attorney General appointed|publisher=Government website|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Attorney for suspect in Cum Ex case===\n\nOn 10 December 2019, Danish media claimed that Geoffrey Cox, as a leading barrister and based on his financial interest declaration to Parliament, had earned 380,000 GBP (3.4 million DKK)<ref name=DR2/> in legal fees during the years 2015-2017 for representing [[Sanjay Shah]], a Dubai-based British businessman and prime suspect in what is reported to have been the [[CumEx-Files|largest tax fraud case]] Denmark has ever seen.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cphpost.dk/news/missing-billions-a-headache-for-danish-tax-authority.html |title=Tax authority gunning for British connection in fraud case |first=Christian |last=W |work=The Copenhagen Post |location=Copenhagen |date=21 August 2018 |accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref> Shah and his legal team asserted that he only exploited legal loopholes which Denmark had failed to close.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cphpost.dk/news/business/accused-british-fraudster-maintains-he-was-merely-playing-the-game-according-to-the-rules.html |title=Accused British fraudster maintains he was merely playing the game according to the rules |first=Stephen |last=Gadd |work=The Copenhagen Post |location=Copenhagen |date=21 May 2019 |accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://cphpost.dk/news/missing-billions-a-headache-for-danish-tax-authority.html |title=Missing billions a headache for Danish tax authority |first=Stephen |last=Gadd |work=The Copenhagen Post |location=Copenhagen |date=6 May 2019 |accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Preben Bang Henriksen]], chairman of the legal affairs committee of the Danish Parliament, claimed that Geoffrey Cox' engagement for Shah poses a [[conflict of interest]] or [[judicial disqualification|disqualification]] issue because the Danish investigation is dependent on British assistance. Henriksen feared that the ties between Shah and Cox \"might discourage British authorities from investigating the case as thoroughly as it evidently needed to be\".<ref name=DR1>{{cite news\n| last1        = Lambek\n| first1       = Bj\u00f8rn\n| last2        = Ussing\n| first2       = Jakob\n| last3        = Fastrup\n| first3       = Niels\n| date         = 10 December 2019\n| title        = Britisk toppolitiker tjente millioner som r\u00e5dgiver for Sanjay Shah\n| trans-title  = British top politician earned millions as a legal adviser for Sanjay Shah\n| url          =https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/penge/britisk-toppolitiker-tjente-millioner-som-raadgiver-sanjay-shah\n| language     = Danish\n| work         =[[Danish Broadcasting Corporation]]\n| location     = Copenhagen\n| access-date  =10 December 2019\n}}</ref> A spokesman for Cox rejected that Cox had influenced the investigation in Britain or Denmark, since a system at the Attorney General office would prevent conflicts of interest because Cox would not take part in any decisions within cases where he had previously been involved as a lawyer.<ref name=DR2>{{cite news\n| last1        = Lambek\n| first1       = Bj\u00f8rn\n| last2        = Ussing\n| first2       = Jakob\n| last3        = Fastrup\n| first3       = Niels\n| date         = 10 December 2019\n| title        = Portr\u00e6t: Kul\u00f8rt topadvokat og politiker har forbindelser til Shah\n| trans-title  = Portrait: Colourful top lawyer and politician has ties to Sanjay Shah\n| url          =https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/penge/britisk-toppolitiker-tjente-millioner-som-raadgiver-sanjay-shah\n| language     = Danish\n| work         =[[Danish Broadcasting Corporation]]\n| location     = Copenhagen\n| access-date  =10 December 2019\n}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nCox lives in rural [[West Devon]], near [[Tavistock]], and London. As with the majority of MPs who do not represent a constituency close to Parliament, he maintains accommodation on expenses in London for when he is working there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/geoffrey-cox/|title=IPSA record|publisher=IPSA|date= |accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref> He married Jeanie MacDonald in 1985 and they have one daughter and two sons.<ref name=UKWW/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geoffreycox.co.uk/about|title=About Geoffrey|publisher=Personal website|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Tax avoidance allegations===\nIn September 2014, it was reported that Cox was one of a number of individuals investing in the Phoenix Film Partners LLC scheme run by Ingenious PLC which [[HM Revenue and Customs]] (HMRC) had alleged to be a [[tax avoidance]] scheme. Ingenious has contested the allegation and claimed the scheme had been submitted to HMRC for pre-approval and that HMRC had not raised any objections. Cox has said that if the scheme was a tax avoidance scheme, it would have contradicted his instructions to his financial advisers, to whom he specified that he did not wish to be involved in aggressive tax avoidance.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.northdevonjournal.co.uk/HMRC-probes-company-MP-Geoffrey-Cox-invested/story-22937353-detail/story.html |title=HMRC probes company in which MP Geoffrey Cox invested |work=North Devon Journal |first=Faye |last=Greenwell|date=17 September 2014|accessdate=1 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150402093136/http://www.northdevonjournal.co.uk/HMRC-probes-company-MP-Geoffrey-Cox-invested/story-22937353-detail/story.html |archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> Following a string of court victories against the schemes, HM Revenue & Customs has since sought to settle disputes with those involved in the tax avoidance, with an agreed re-payment package. Ingenious PLC were reported to still be disputing the claims.<ref>{{cite news |title=HMRC offers film partnerships an end to tax saga |url= https://www.ft.com/content/5674d898-ba04-11e5-bf7e-8a339b6f2164 |work=Financial Times |location= London |accessdate=9 September 2018 |date=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{commons category|Geoffrey Cox}}\n* [http://www.geoffreycox.co.uk Geoffrey Cox QC MP] \u2013 Parliamentary site\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=mr-geoffrey-cox/1508 |publicwhip=Geoffrey_Cox |theywork=geoffrey_cox}}\n* [http://www.thomasmore.co.uk/ Thomas More Chambers] \u2013 Chambers of Geoffrey Cox QC MP\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050506212456/https://www.conservatives.com/tile.do?def=people.person.page&PersonID=34014 Conservative Party \u2013 Geoffrey Cox MP] \u2013 biography\n* [http://www.westdevonconservatives.com/ Torridge and West Devon Conservatives] \u2013 constituency site\n* [https://archive.is/20150412104809/http://www.votegeoffreycox.co.uk/ Geoffrey Cox for Torridge and West Devon] \u2013 2015 campaign website\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100505135205/http://www.geoffreycox.net/ Geoffrey Cox \u2013 Conservative Candidate for Torridge and West Devon] \u2013 2010 campaign website\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-6147,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics \u2013 Ask Aristotle: Geoffrey Cox MP]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/devon/7099754.stm Heating grants in November 2007]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/devon/6179862.stm Appledore shipyard in November 2006]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Burnett, Baron Burnett|John Burnett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Torridge and West Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|Torridge and West Devon]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Jeremy Wright]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney General for England and Wales]]|years=2018\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Suella Braverman]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Advocate General for Northern Ireland]]|years=2018\u20132020}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Johnson Cabinet}}\n{{South West Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cox, Geoffrey}}\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Downing College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People educated at King's College, Taunton]]\n[[Category:People from Wroughton]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 2001\u2013]]\n[[Category:English Queen's Counsel]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Geoffrey Cox\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|QC}} [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Geoffrey Cox QC MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption =\n| office = [[Attorney General for England and Wales]]<br />[[Advocate General for Northern Ireland]]\n| primeminister = [[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 9 July 2018\n| term_end = 13 February 2020\n| predecessor = [[Jeremy Wright]]\n| successor = [[Suella Braverman]]\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Torridge and West Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|Torridge and West Devon]]\n| parliament1 = \n| term_start1 = 5 May 2005\n| term_end1 =\n| majority1 = 24,992 (41.8%)\n| predecessor1 = [[John Burnett, Baron Burnett|John Burnett]]\n| successor1 =\n|birth_name=Charles Geoffrey Cox\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1960|04|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Wroughton]], [[Wiltshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = Jeanie Cox\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations = \n| children = 3\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Downing College, Cambridge]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = {{URL|www.geoffreycox.co.uk}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Charles Geoffrey Cox''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|QC}}<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59418 |date=13 May 2010 |page=8741}}</ref> (born 30 April 1960) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician and [[barrister]] serving as [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Torridge and West Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|Torridge and West Devon]] since the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]]. Cox worked as a barrister from 1982 onwards and was appointed a [[Queen's Counsel]] in 2003, two years before his election to Parliament. On 9 July 2018, he was appointed [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] and gave up private practice; prior to this he had been the highest earning MP in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|title=The richest MPs in Britain based on income|url= http://uk.businessinsider.com/the-richest-mp-in-terms-of-second-incomes-2017-8/#3-kenneth-clarke-conservative-274800-mostly-from-his-autobiography-deal-11|work=Business Insider|accessdate=16 August 2018|date=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nCharles Geoffrey Cox was born in [[Wroughton]], [[Wiltshire]] on 30 April 1960 to Michael (a Royal Artillery Officer) and Diane Cox. He was educated at [[King's College, Taunton]], an [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent school]] in Somerset. He studied law and classics at [[Downing College, Cambridge]].<ref name=UKWW>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-2000219?rskey=ubli0k&result=3|publisher=UK Who's Who|accessdate=25 September 2019|title=Cox, Rt Hon. (Charles) Geoffrey}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/geoffrey-cox-profile-from-back-benches-to-eye-of-the-storm-p53xhdhbz |title=Geoffrey Cox profile: from back benches to eye of the storm |work=The Times |location= London |date=13 March 2019 |last=Zeffman |first=Henry}}{{subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\n\n[[Called to the Bar]] at the [[Middle Temple]] in 1982, Cox started practice as a barrister; in 1992 he co-founded Thomas More Chambers, serving as its Head of Chambers. He was appointed [[Queen's Counsel]] in 2003.<ref name=geof>{{cite web|url=http://www.thomasmore.co.uk/members/geoffrey_cox_qc |title=Thomas More Chambers: Geoffrey Cox QC |accessdate=24 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129222634/http://www.thomasmore.co.uk/members/geoffrey_cox_qc |archivedate=29 November 2014  }}</ref>\n\nFor part of his career as a barrister, Cox was Standing Counsel to the government of the [[Indian Ocean]] island nation of [[Mauritius]]. His cases have included \"civil fraud and asset recovery, commercial, human rights, defamation, and judicial review actions\". He has frequently appeared as leading counsel in the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]] or the [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council|Privy Council]], and he was increasingly instructed to lead in commercial actions and arbitrations overseas, appearing in the [[Dubai International Financial Centre|DIFC]], Mauritius and the [[Cayman Islands]].<ref name=geof/>\n\nHis criminal cases have included the [[Jubilee line corruption trial]]; representing Virendra Rastogi the owner of [[RBG Resources]];<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/fraudster-tycoon-with-mayfair-flat-is-given-5-million-legal-aid-7499116.html |title=Fraudster tycoon with Mayfair flat is given \u00a35 million legal aid |work=London Evening Standard |date=2 March 2012 |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> and successfully defending a member of the [[Queen's Lancashire Regiment]] who had been accused of [[war crime]]s related to the [[death of Baha Mousa]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Williams |first=A.T. |date=18 October 2012 |title=A Very British Killing |url=https://books.google.com/?id=a19QjWd5f68C&pg=PA200&lpg=PA200&dq=geoffrey+cox+donald+payne#v=onepage&q=geoffrey%20cox%20donald%20payne&f=false |publisher=Jonathan Cape |page=200 |isbn=978-0224096881}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Cox successfully defended the former Premier (and current  Speaker of the Legislative Assembly) of the Cayman Islands, [[McKeeva Bush]], on charges of corruption and misuse of office.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.compasscayman.com/caycompass/2014/10/10/Courtroom-theater-draws-crowds/|title=Courtroom theater draws crowds|author=James Whittaker|work=Cayman Compass|date=10 October 2014|accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref> In March 2015, Cox successfully defended the deputy Editor of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', [[Geoff Webster]], in a trial of four journalists resulting from [[Operation Elveden]].<ref name=beeeb>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-31998319|title=Sun journalist's lawyer queries use of 'vague' law|work=BBC News|date=21 March 2015|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> The jury had to decide at what point the behaviour of those on trial could be considered a criminal rather than a serious disciplinary matter; even the lawyers found this difficult to define.<ref name=lisa>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/mar/20/acquittal-four-senior-sun-journalists-blow-cps |title=Acquittal of four senior Sun journalists seen as blow to CPS |work=The Guardian |location= London |first=Lisa |last=O'Carroll|date=20 March 2015|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> Cox subsequently publicly criticised the vagueness of the law, and its disproportionate use that had led to the prosecution.<ref name=beeeb/>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n[[File:Geoffrey Cox MP hosting Lamerton Hunt 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Cox hosting a lawn meet of the [[Lamerton]] Foxhounds, 2014]]\nCox was first selected to stand for Parliament in 2000 by the Torridge and West Devon Conservatives. In the following [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], he came second to incumbent [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[John Burnett, Baron Burnett|John Burnett]] by 1,194 votes.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/england/4519145.stm |title=One change in Devon political map |publisher=BBC News|date=6 May 2005|accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/results_constituencies/constituencies/191.stm|title=Devon West & Torridge|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2001 election, Cox was reselected. Burnett announced in 2003 that he would not contest the seat again, and at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] Cox defeated the new Liberal Democrat candidate, [[David Walter (British journalist and politician)|David Walter]], gaining a majority of 3,236.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/vote2005/html/191.stm|title=Result: Devon West & Torridge|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=25 September 2019|date=6 May 2005}}</ref> Cox made his [[maiden speech]] in the House of Commons on 28 June 2005.\n\nCox was re-elected as MP for Torridge and West Devon at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] with an increased majority of 18,403 votes (32.5%).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14001000#election2015-logo|title=Devon West & Torridge|accessdate=25 September 2019|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> This majority increased by over 2,000 votes at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 election]] to 20,686 (34.7%).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14001000|title=Devon West & Torridge|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, it was reported he had a number of office expense claims for items, such as a 49p pint of milk, rejected by the Commons authorities. He was criticised for this as at the time Cox was Britain's highest-paid MP. In response, Cox said that his staff had been unaware of a recent change in the rules for office expenses, which no longer permitted office hospitality items such as tea, coffee or milk to be claimed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Geoffrey Cox: Tory MP has expenses claim for 49p pint of milk rejected by Commons |first=Andy |last=McSmith |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/geoffrey-cox-tory-mp-has-expenses-claim-for-49p-pint-of-milk-rejected-by-commons-a6813131.html |work=The Independent |location= London |accessdate=9 September 2018|date=14 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Cox was one of 72 MPs who were themselves landlords who derived an income from a property and who backed the Conservative Government in voting down an amendment in Parliament on rental homes being \"fit for human habitation\". The Government argued that the law already provided more effective remedies for tenants to report homes in bad repair to local authorities who then had a statutory duty to inspect them and to take action against the landlord, and that the previous Labour Government had for the same reason rejected the proposal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tories vote down law requiring landlords make their homes fit for human habitation |first=Jon |last=Stone |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tories-vote-down-law-requiring-landlords-make-their-homes-fit-for-human-habitation-a6809691.html |work=The Independent |location= London |accessdate=9 September 2018 |date=13 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Cox told the House of Commons that he had concluded, after examining the published renegotiation proposals, that the case for leaving the EU was now overwhelming and that he would vote to do so in the forthcoming [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geoffreycox.co.uk/content/eu-renegotiation-0|title=EU Renegotiation|publisher=Personal website|accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July 2018, Cox was appointed to the Cabinet as Her Majesty's Attorney General for England and Wales and Advocate General for Northern Ireland.\n\nIn the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] he has sat on the [[Department for the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]] [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|Select committee]], the Committee on Standards and the Committee on Privileges.<ref name=parliamentbiocox>{{cite web|title=Geoffrey Cox|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/geoffrey-cox/1508|website=Parliament UK|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref> Cox resigned from the latter role in 2016 after registering more than \u00a3400,000 of outside earnings within the time limit. <ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/12188113/MPs-must-no-longer-police-themselves.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=9 March 2016|accessdate=25 September 2019 |title=MPs must no longer police themselves, says sleaze watchdog Lord Bew |last1=Malnick |first1=Edward |last2=Newell |first2=Claire}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2019 General Election, Geoffrey Cox was re-elected with 60.1% of the vote and a majority of 24,992 (41.8%).\n\n===Attorney General===\n\nOn 9 July 2018, [[Theresa May]] appointed Cox as [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] (the government's top law officer) taking over from [[Jeremy Wright]] following a [[Cabinet reshuffle]], prompted by the resignations of [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]] and [[Boris Johnson]].\n\nOn 1 December 2018, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' newspaper reported the leaked contents of a recent Geoffrey Cox letter to Cabinet Ministers detailing the Attorney General's legal advice on Theresa May's Brexit deal. The newspaper reported that his legal advice declared the Withdrawal agreement's backstop protocol would mean the UK being indefinitely locked into a customs union with the EU if future negotiations collapse and that the only way the UK could leave the Backstop would be the signing of a future trade deal which could take many years to complete. The former [[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|Brexit Secretary]] [[Dominic Raab]] and three serving Cabinet members confirmed the contents of the letter to the ''Sunday Times''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Shipman |title=Revealed: Brexit legal advice could sink Theresa May |url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/revealed-brexit-legal-advice-could-sink-theresa-may-r9wmh0v89 |work=The Sunday Times |location= London |date=2 December 2018 }}{{subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Theresa May placed Cox in charge of negotiating changes to the [[Northern Ireland backstop]] in the [[European Union|EU]] [[Brexit withdrawal agreement|withdrawal agreement]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47409659 |title=May's fate in the hands of the 'showman' |work=BBC News |last=Watt |first=Nicholas |date=28 February 2019 |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 September 2019, the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] ruled unanimously that Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]]'s [[2019 British prorogation controversy|prorogation of parliament]] was unlawful overturning the High Court\u2019s judgment, given by the Lord Chief Justice, in the government\u2019s favour. On the same day, minutes of a conference call between cabinet ministers (which included Cox) were leaked to [[Sky News]]. The minutes of the call, which took place after the prorogation had been approved by the Queen, detailed that Cox briefly told the cabinet at that time that in his view the prorogation was lawful and constitutional and that any accusations of unlawfulness \"were motivated by political considerations\". Cox\u2019s full advice to the Government has not been published.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/exclusive-pm-was-advised-by-attorney-general-suspension-was-lawful-11818599|title=Exclusive: PM was advised by attorney general suspension was 'lawful' |website=Sky News |access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> The next day Cox appeared in the House of Commons to answer an urgent question on the Government's legal advice and on the implications of the Supreme Court's decision. Cox rebutted calls for him to resign and criticisms of the Government's position, pointing out that senior and distinguished judges had agreed with the Government's view that the issue was not justiciable and chiding MPs for refusing to agree to a means of the UK leaving the EU while repeatedly preventing the House of Commons from dissolving for an election.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/quentin-letts-sketch-verbal-barrage-from-the-flawed-projector-plv0fx9c3{{paywall}}</ref>{{verification-inline|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn February 2020 Cox said the public is concerned about the creeping \"judicialisation of politics\" and said people were right to worry that unelected officials were taking decisions that ought to be taken by Parliament. He promised there would not be radical reforms. He stated his opposition to the highly politicised US selection process of [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] and suggested he preferred the Canadian system. Cox said  that \"there's a case for looking at how supreme court judges are appointed... There's a committee of the Canadian parliament that carries out interviews [of candidates].\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/12/geoffrey-cox-signals-would-accept-lead-role-review-judiciary]</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51474169]</ref>\n\nOn 13 February 2020, the ''[[Financial Times]]''{{'}}s Whitehall correspondent reported that Cox had been sacked as Attorney General.\n\n==Outside work whilst employed as an MP==\n\nCox has continued to practise as a Queen's Counsel whilst an MP.<ref name=geof/> According to ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', based on the declarations in the Register of Members' Interests, Cox's extra-parliamentary work was worth \u00a3820,867 in 2014, or 12 times his annual MP salary, whilst the total time on extra-parliamentary work that was registered in 2014 (although the register shows the hours were worked over 3 years) was 1,954 hours.<ref name=lyn>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/investigations/11428075/The-MPs-who-topped-up-their-salaries-with-1600-an-hour-second-jobs.html |title=The MPs who topped up their salaries with \u00a31,600-an-hour second jobs |first1=Lyndsey |last1=Telford |first2=Luke |last2=Heighton |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=22 February 2015 |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> According to the  Register as of 2 July 2018], his extra-parliamentary earnings in the 12 months from July 2017 to June 2018 were \u00a3487,043; the time expended totalled 1,070 hours, carried out over several years.<ref>{{cite web |title=House of Commons - The Register of Members' Financial Interests (2 July 2018: Cox, Mr Geoffrey ) |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmregmem/180702/cox_geoffrey.htm |website=publications.parliament.uk |language=English}}</ref>\n\nCox has previously defended his outside work, pointing out that MPs of all parties have practised as QCs over the years, and that the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] and [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor General]] are normally chosen from their ranks.<ref name=west/> He has argued that he has always been used to long hours, 70 and 80 hour weeks were quite normal at the Bar, and that the [[Committee on Standards in Public Life|Nolan report]] concluded that Parliament needed people with current experience of a wide range of professional and other backgrounds.<ref name=west>{{cite news |url= http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Experience-world-work-lost-Commons/story-19179766-detail/story.html |title=Experience of world of work must not be lost in Commons |work= Western Morning News |location=Plymouth |first=Geoffrey |last=Cox |date=4 June 2013 |accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the House of Commons [[Commons Select Committee on Standards|Standards Committee]]\u2014of which he was a member\u2014found that he had committed a serious breach of a House of Commons rule, designed to make transparent an MP's financial interests, after failing to register \u00a3400k of outside earnings (11 payments) for legal work within the permitted 28-day period. Cox registered the payments late, variously between two and seven months after the deadline; he said that he had omitted to prioritise the rule in the midst of an intense political and professional schedule. When first registering the payments, in September 2015, Cox drew attention to and apologised to the Registrar for his omission, referring himself to the [[Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards|Parliamentary Commissioner]], and stepped down from the Committee.\n\nThe Commissioner and the Committee accepted that the payments had not in fact given rise to any conflicts of interest, and that the failure to register the payments within 28 days had thus had no practical effect. [[Alistair Graham]], the former Chairman of the [[Committee on Standards in Public Life]], criticised the lack of punishment and called for a complete reform, while [[Martin Bell]] said the Committee on Standards had a long history of inflicting light punishment, which showed that the House was incapable of regulating itself.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/conservative-mps-expenses/12140118/Tory-MP-Geoffrey-Cox-will-only-have-to-apologise-after-failing-to-declare-hundreds-of-thousands-of-pounds.html |title=Tory MP Geoffrey Cox will only have to apologise after failing to declare hundreds of thousands of pounds |first=Laura |last=Hughes |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=4 February 2016 |accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July 2018, Cox gave up all private practice upon his appointment as Attorney General.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-attorney-general-appointed|title= New Attorney General appointed|publisher=Government website|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Attorney for suspect in Cum Ex case===\n\nOn 10 December 2019, Danish media claimed that Geoffrey Cox, as a leading barrister and based on his financial interest declaration to Parliament, had earned 380,000 GBP (3.4 million DKK)<ref name=DR2/> in legal fees during the years 2015-2017 for representing [[Sanjay Shah]], a Dubai-based British businessman and prime suspect in what is reported to have been the [[CumEx-Files|largest tax fraud case]] Denmark has ever seen.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cphpost.dk/news/missing-billions-a-headache-for-danish-tax-authority.html |title=Tax authority gunning for British connection in fraud case |first=Christian |last=W |work=The Copenhagen Post |location=Copenhagen |date=21 August 2018 |accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref> Shah and his legal team asserted that he only exploited legal loopholes which Denmark had failed to close.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cphpost.dk/news/business/accused-british-fraudster-maintains-he-was-merely-playing-the-game-according-to-the-rules.html |title=Accused British fraudster maintains he was merely playing the game according to the rules |first=Stephen |last=Gadd |work=The Copenhagen Post |location=Copenhagen |date=21 May 2019 |accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://cphpost.dk/news/missing-billions-a-headache-for-danish-tax-authority.html |title=Missing billions a headache for Danish tax authority |first=Stephen |last=Gadd |work=The Copenhagen Post |location=Copenhagen |date=6 May 2019 |accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Preben Bang Henriksen]], chairman of the legal affairs committee of the Danish Parliament, claimed that Geoffrey Cox' engagement for Shah poses a [[conflict of interest]] or [[judicial disqualification|disqualification]] issue because the Danish investigation is dependent on British assistance. Henriksen feared that the ties between Shah and Cox \"might discourage British authorities from investigating the case as thoroughly as it evidently needed to be\".<ref name=DR1>{{cite news\n| last1        = Lambek\n| first1       = Bj\u00f8rn\n| last2        = Ussing\n| first2       = Jakob\n| last3        = Fastrup\n| first3       = Niels\n| date         = 10 December 2019\n| title        = Britisk toppolitiker tjente millioner som r\u00e5dgiver for Sanjay Shah\n| trans-title  = British top politician earned millions as a legal adviser for Sanjay Shah\n| url          =https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/penge/britisk-toppolitiker-tjente-millioner-som-raadgiver-sanjay-shah\n| language     = Danish\n| work         =[[Danish Broadcasting Corporation]]\n| location     = Copenhagen\n| access-date  =10 December 2019\n}}</ref> A spokesman for Cox rejected that Cox had influenced the investigation in Britain or Denmark, since a system at the Attorney General office would prevent conflicts of interest because Cox would not take part in any decisions within cases where he had previously been involved as a lawyer.<ref name=DR2>{{cite news\n| last1        = Lambek\n| first1       = Bj\u00f8rn\n| last2        = Ussing\n| first2       = Jakob\n| last3        = Fastrup\n| first3       = Niels\n| date         = 10 December 2019\n| title        = Portr\u00e6t: Kul\u00f8rt topadvokat og politiker har forbindelser til Shah\n| trans-title  = Portrait: Colourful top lawyer and politician has ties to Sanjay Shah\n| url          =https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/penge/britisk-toppolitiker-tjente-millioner-som-raadgiver-sanjay-shah\n| language     = Danish\n| work         =[[Danish Broadcasting Corporation]]\n| location     = Copenhagen\n| access-date  =10 December 2019\n}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nCox lives in rural [[West Devon]], near [[Tavistock]], and London. As with the majority of MPs who do not represent a constituency close to Parliament, he maintains accommodation on expenses in London for when he is working there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/geoffrey-cox/|title=IPSA record|publisher=IPSA|date= |accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref> He married Jeanie MacDonald in 1985 and they have one daughter and two sons.<ref name=UKWW/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geoffreycox.co.uk/about|title=About Geoffrey|publisher=Personal website|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Tax avoidance allegations===\nIn September 2014, it was reported that Cox was one of a number of individuals investing in the Phoenix Film Partners LLC scheme run by Ingenious PLC which [[HM Revenue and Customs]] (HMRC) had alleged to be a [[tax avoidance]] scheme. Ingenious has contested the allegation and claimed the scheme had been submitted to HMRC for pre-approval and that HMRC had not raised any objections. Cox has said that if the scheme was a tax avoidance scheme, it would have contradicted his instructions to his financial advisers, to whom he specified that he did not wish to be involved in aggressive tax avoidance.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.northdevonjournal.co.uk/HMRC-probes-company-MP-Geoffrey-Cox-invested/story-22937353-detail/story.html |title=HMRC probes company in which MP Geoffrey Cox invested |work=North Devon Journal |first=Faye |last=Greenwell|date=17 September 2014|accessdate=1 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150402093136/http://www.northdevonjournal.co.uk/HMRC-probes-company-MP-Geoffrey-Cox-invested/story-22937353-detail/story.html |archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> Following a string of court victories against the schemes, HM Revenue & Customs has since sought to settle disputes with those involved in the tax avoidance, with an agreed re-payment package. Ingenious PLC were reported to still be disputing the claims.<ref>{{cite news |title=HMRC offers film partnerships an end to tax saga |url= https://www.ft.com/content/5674d898-ba04-11e5-bf7e-8a339b6f2164 |work=Financial Times |location= London |accessdate=9 September 2018 |date=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{commons category|Geoffrey Cox}}\n* [http://www.geoffreycox.co.uk Geoffrey Cox QC MP] \u2013 Parliamentary site\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=mr-geoffrey-cox/1508 |publicwhip